{"title_page": "Desolation Angels (1995 film)", "text_new": "{{Infobox film\n|name=Desolation Angels\n|director=[[Tim McCann (director)|Tim McCann]]\n|writer=Tim McCann\n|producer=\n|starring=[[Michael Rodrick]]<br>Jennifer Thomas<br>Peter Bassett\n|released=1995\n|country=[[United States]]\n|language=English\n}}\n\n'''''Desolation Angels''''' is a 1995 independent film written and directed by [[Tim McCann (director)|Tim McCann]].<ref name=nytimes>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/05/05/nyregion/film-wins-many-accolades-but-few-rewards-for-maker.html | title=Film Wins Many Accolades But Few Rewards for Maker| first=Ann|last=Costello|work=[[The New York Times]] | date=May 5, 1996| accessdate= January 20, 2016| quote=Mr. Demme was host to a private screening of 'Desolation Angels' last summer.... The date was June 21, Mr. McCann's 30th birthday.| archivedate= May 26, 2015| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150526160944/http://www.nytimes.com/1996/05/05/nyregion/film-wins-many-accolades-but-few-rewards-for-maker.html | url-status=live}} Note: Source says, \"Mr. McCann won the top prize, the Merchant/Ivory Award, in October after his movie had its premiere before packed audiences in Telluride.\" The 1995 Telluride Film Festival [http://www.filmscouts.com/scripts/festival.cfm was held in September 1995] and has no \"Merchant/Ivory Award\".</ref>\n\nThe film premiered at the 1995 [[Telluride Film Festival]].<ref name=nytimes /><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.filmscouts.com/scripts/festarchive.cfm?name=telluride/films#desol | title=Film Programs: 1995 Telluride Film Festival | publisher=FilmScout.com | accessdate=January 21, 2016 | archivedate=October 18, 2006 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061018102919/http://www.filmscouts.com/scripts/festarchive.cfm?name=telluride%2Ffilms#desol | url-status=live }}</ref> It then won the International Critics Prize (FIPRESCI Prize) at the [[Toronto International Film Festival]],<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.fipresci.org/awards/1995 | publisher=FIPRESCI (F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de la Presse Cin\u00e9matographique / The International Federation of Film Critics)| title=Awards > '90s | accessdate= January 21, 2016| archivedate= September 13, 2015 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150913043622/http://www.fipresci.org/awards/1995 | url-status=live}}</ref> and was accepted to the [[Rotterdam Film Festival]].<ref name=nytimes />\n\n==Plot==\nReturning home from a trip to visit his mother, Nick ([[Michael Rodrick]]) discovers that a good friend of his, Sid (Peter Bassett), has apparently raped Nick's girlfriend, Mary (Jennifer Thomas). More concerned with his own wounded pride than with Mary's lingering feelings of guilt, pain and betrayal, Nick vows revenge.\n\n==Reception==\nIn his review of ''Desolation Angels'' for ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', [[Peter Travers]] declared that \"male ego is the demon in this blazingly provocative debut film from the gifted Tim McCann,\" and concluded that viewers \"won\u2019t stop talking about this one.\"<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.timmccannfilm.com/films#/desolation-angels | publisher=Tim McCann| title=FILMS \u2014 TIM MCCANN | accessdate= April 17, 2020| url-status=live}}</ref> Michael Wilmington of the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' praised the film as \"an ultra-low budget drama of considerable accomplishment and sometimes extraordinary power\" and wrote, \"This is probably as devastating a portrayal and indictment of modern male insensitivity as any film has given us recently... One of the year\u2019s more impressive debuts.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1996-10-06-9610060279-story.html | title='ANGELS' PACKS A JOLT| first=Michael|last=Wilmington|work=[[Chicago Tribune]] | date=October 6, 1996| accessdate= April 17, 2020| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|0116085}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes| m/desolation_angels | Desolation Angels}}\n\n[[Category:1995 films]]\n[[Category:American thriller films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:1990s independent films]]\n[[Category:American independent films]]\n[[Category:1990s thriller films]]\n\n\n{{indie-film-stub}}\n{{1990s-thriller-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox film\n|name=Desolation Angels\n|director=[[Tim McCann (director)|Tim McCann]]\n|writer=Tim McCann\n|producer=\n|starring=[[Michael Rodrick]]<br>Jennifer Thomas<br>[[Peter Bassett]]\n|released=1995\n|country=[[United States]]\n|language=English\n}}\n\n'''''Desolation Angels''''' is a 1995 independent film written and directed by [[Tim McCann (director)|Tim McCann]].<ref name=nytimes>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/05/05/nyregion/film-wins-many-accolades-but-few-rewards-for-maker.html | title=Film Wins Many Accolades But Few Rewards for Maker| first=Ann|last=Costello|work=[[The New York Times]] | date=May 5, 1996| accessdate= January 20, 2016| quote=Mr. Demme was host to a private screening of 'Desolation Angels' last summer.... The date was June 21, Mr. McCann's 30th birthday.| archivedate= May 26, 2015| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150526160944/http://www.nytimes.com/1996/05/05/nyregion/film-wins-many-accolades-but-few-rewards-for-maker.html | url-status=live}} Note: Source says, \"Mr. McCann won the top prize, the Merchant/Ivory Award, in October after his movie had its premiere before packed audiences in Telluride.\" The 1995 Telluride Film Festival [http://www.filmscouts.com/scripts/festival.cfm was held in September 1995] and has no \"Merchant/Ivory Award\".</ref>\n\nThe film premiered at the 1995 [[Telluride Film Festival]].<ref name=nytimes /><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.filmscouts.com/scripts/festarchive.cfm?name=telluride/films#desol | title=Film Programs: 1995 Telluride Film Festival | publisher=FilmScout.com | accessdate=January 21, 2016 | archivedate=October 18, 2006 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061018102919/http://www.filmscouts.com/scripts/festarchive.cfm?name=telluride%2Ffilms#desol | url-status=live }}</ref> It then won the International Critics Prize (FIPRESCI Prize) at the [[Toronto International Film Festival]],<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.fipresci.org/awards/1995 | publisher=FIPRESCI (F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de la Presse Cin\u00e9matographique / The International Federation of Film Critics)| title=Awards > '90s | accessdate= January 21, 2016| archivedate= September 13, 2015 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150913043622/http://www.fipresci.org/awards/1995 | url-status=live}}</ref> and was accepted to the [[Rotterdam Film Festival]].<ref name=nytimes />\n\n==Plot==\nReturning home from a trip to visit his mother, Nick ([[Michael Rodrick]]) discovers that a good friend of his, Sid ([[Peter Bassett]]), has apparently raped Nick's girlfriend, Mary (Jennifer Thomas). More concerned with his own wounded pride than with Mary's lingering feelings of guilt, pain and betrayal, Nick vows revenge.\n\n==Reception==\nIn his review of ''Desolation Angels'' for ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', [[Peter Travers]] declared that \"male ego is the demon in this blazingly provocative debut film from the gifted Tim McCann,\" and concluded that viewers \"won\u2019t stop talking about this one.\"<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.timmccannfilm.com/films#/desolation-angels | publisher=Tim McCann| title=FILMS \u2014 TIM MCCANN | accessdate= April 17, 2020| url-status=live}}</ref> Michael Wilmington of the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' praised the film as \"an ultra-low budget drama of considerable accomplishment and sometimes extraordinary power\" and wrote, \"This is probably as devastating a portrayal and indictment of modern male insensitivity as any film has given us recently... One of the year\u2019s more impressive debuts.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1996-10-06-9610060279-story.html | title='ANGELS' PACKS A JOLT| first=Michael|last=Wilmington|work=[[Chicago Tribune]] | date=October 6, 1996| accessdate= April 17, 2020| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|0116085}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes| m/desolation_angels | Desolation Angels}}\n\n[[Category:1995 films]]\n[[Category:American thriller films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:1990s independent films]]\n[[Category:American independent films]]\n[[Category:1990s thriller films]]\n\n\n{{indie-film-stub}}\n{{1990s-thriller-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Kturnkturn", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removed links that were leading to an unrelated, historical person", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Desolation_Angels_(1995_film)"}
{"title_page": "Richmond, Virginia", "text_new": "{{Short description|Capital of Virginia}}\n{{distinguish|Richmond County, Virginia}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use American English|date=August 2015}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                     = Richmond, Virginia\n| official_name            = City of Richmond\n| settlement_type          = [[List of capitals in the United States|State capital]] and [[independent city (United States)|independent city]]\n| image_skyline            = Collage of Landmarks in Richmond, Virginia v 1.jpg\n| imagesize                = 300px\n| image_caption            = Top: [[Downtown Richmond, Virginia|Downtown]] skyline above the falls of the [[James River]] Middle: [[St. John's Episcopal Church (Richmond, Virginia)|St. John's Episcopal Church]], [[Jackson Ward]], [[Monument Avenue]]. Bottom: [[Virginia State Capitol]], [[Main Street Station (Richmond, Virginia)|Main Street Station]]\n| image_flag               = Flag of Richmond, Virginia.jpg\n| image_seal               = Seal of Richmond, Virginia.png\n| nickname                 = \"RVA\", \"The River City\"<ref>''City Connection'', Office of the Press Secretary to the Mayor. [http://www.richmondgov.com/PressSecretaryMayor/documents/CityConnection.pdf#page=2 Richmondgov.com] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110930174829/http://www.richmondgov.com/PressSecretaryMayor/documents/CityConnection.pdf#page=2 |date=September 30, 2011 }}. January\u2013March 2010 edition. Retrieved February 8, 2010.</ref>{{Failed verification|date=January 2019}}\n| motto                    = {{lang-la|Sic Itur Ad Astra}}<br />(Thus do we reach the stars)\n| image_map                = \n| mapsize                  = 250 px\n| map_caption              = Location within Virginia\n| pushpin_map = Virginia#USA\n| pushpin_label = Richmond\n| pushpin_map_caption = Location within Virginia##Location within the contiguous United States\n| pushpin_relief           = yes\n| coordinates    