trict !! VLR!! NRHP\n|-\n| [[Barret House (Richmond, Virginia)|The Barret House]] (15 South Fifth Street) || 1971 || [https://web.archive.org/web/20160506000738/http://www.dhr.virginia.gov/registers/Cities/Richmond/127-0029_Barret_House_1972_Final_Nomination.pdf 1972]\n|-\n| [[Belgian Building]] (Lombardy Street and Brook Road)||1969||[https://web.archive.org/web/20160506014049/http://www.dhr.virginia.gov/registers/Cities/Richmond/127-0173_Belgian_Building_1970_Final_Nomination.pdf 1970]\n|-\n| [[Bolling Haxall House]] (211 East Franklin Street)||1971||[https://web.archive.org/web/20160304052030/http://www.dhr.virginia.gov/registers/Cities/Richmond/127-0033_Haxall,Bolling,House_1972_Final_Nomination.pdf 1972]\n|-\n| [[Centenary United Methodist Church]] (409 East Grace Street)||1979||[https://web.archive.org/web/20160506000719/http://www.dhr.virginia.gov/registers/Cities/Richmond/127-0321_Centenary_Church_1979_Final_Nomination.pdf 1979]\n|-\n| [[Crozet House]] (100\u2013102 East Main Street)||1971||[https://web.archive.org/web/20120927033802/http://www.dhr.virginia.gov/registers/Cities/Richmond/127-0047_Crozet_House_1972_Final_Nomination.pdf 1972]\n|-\n| [[Ellen Glasgow House|Glasgow House]] (1 West Main Street)||1972||[https://web.archive.org/web/20160506014445/http://www.dhr.virginia.gov/registers/Cities/Richmond/127-0056_EllenGlasgowHouse_1972_Final_Nomination_NHL.pdf 1972]\n|-\n| [[Hancock-Wirt-Caskie House]] (2 North Fifth Street)||1969||[https://web.archive.org/web/20120927070838/http://www.dhr.virginia.gov/registers/Cities/Richmond/127-0042_William_Wirt_House_1970_Final_Nomination.pdf 1970] [https://web.archive.org/web/20120927070841/http://www.dhr.virginia.gov/registers/Cities/Richmond/127-0042_Hancock_Wirt_Caskie_House_AdditionalDoc_2008_NR_final.pdf 2008]\n|-\n| [[Henry Coalter Cabell House]] (116 South Third Street)||1971||[https://web.archive.org/web/20120927033355/http://www.dhr.virginia.gov/registers/Cities/Richmond/127-0225_HenryCoalterCabellHouse_1972_Final_Nomination.pdf 1971]\n|-\n| [[Jefferson Hotel (Richmond, Virginia)|Jefferson Hotel]] (114 West Main Street)||1968||[https://web.archive.org/web/20160505181502/http://www.dhr.virginia.gov/registers/Cities/Richmond/127-0001_Jefferson_Hotel_1968_NRHP_Final.pdf 1969]\n|-\n| [[John Marshall House]] (818 East Marshall Street)||1969||[https://web.archive.org/web/20160505083251/http://www.dhr.virginia.gov/registers/Cities/Richmond/127-0073_John_Marshall_House_1972_Final_Nomination_NHL.pdf 1966]\n|-\n| [[Leigh Street Baptist Church]] (East Leigh and Twenty-Fifth Streets)||1971||[https://web.archive.org/web/20120927035357/http://www.dhr.virginia.gov/registers/Cities/Richmond/127-0011_Leigh_St_Baptist_Church_1972_Final_Nomination.pdf 1972]\n|-\n| [[Linden Row]] (100\u2013114 East Franklin Street)||1971||[https://web.archive.org/web/20160304065953/http://www.dhr.virginia.gov/registers/Cities/Richmond/127-0022_Linden_Row_1971_Final_Nomination.pdf 1971]\n|-\n| [[Taylor-Mayo House|Mayo Memorial House]] (110 West Franklin Street)||1972||[https://web.archive.org/web/20120927035757/http://www.dhr.virginia.gov/registers/Cities/Richmond/127-0075_Mayo_Memorial_Church_House_1973_Final_Nomination.pdf 1973]\n|-\n| William W. Morien House (2226 West Main Street)||||\n|-\n| [[Stewart-Lee House|Norman Stewart House]] (707 East Franklin Street)||1972||[https://web.archive.org/web/20120927041441/http://www.dhr.virginia.gov/registers/Cities/Richmond/127-0064_Stewart-Lee_House_1972_Final_Nomination.pdf 1972]\n|-\n| [[Edgar Allan Poe Museum (Richmond, Virginia)#Old Stone House|Old Stone House]] (1916 East Main Street)||1973||[https://web.archive.org/web/20160506014235/http://www.dhr.virginia.gov/registers/Cities/Richmond/127-0100_Old_Stone_House_1973_Final_Nomination.pdf 1973]\n|-\n| Pace House (100 West Franklin Street)||||\n|-\n| [[St. Andrew's Church (Richmond, Virginia)|St. Andrew's Episcopal Church]] (Northwest corner South Laurel Street and Idlewood Avenue)||1979||[https://web.archive.org/web/20160512131723/http://www.dhr.virginia.gov/registers/Cities/Richmond/127-0314_St_Andrew%27s_Episcopal_Church_Complex_1979_Final_Nomination.pdf 1979]\n|-\n| [[St. Paul's Episcopal Church (Richmond, Virginia)|St. Paul's Episcopal Church]] (815 East Grace Street)||1968||[https://web.archive.org/web/20100818051941/http://www.dhr.virginia.gov/registers/Cities/Richmond/127-0014_St_Pauls_Church_1969_Nomination.pdf 1969]\n|-\n| [[St. Peter's Church (Richmond, Virginia)|St. Peter's Catholic Church]] (800 East Grace Street)||1968||[https://web.archive.org/web/20160304040348/http://www.dhr.virginia.gov/registers/Cities/Richmond/127-0015_Saint_Peter's_Church_1969_Final_Nomination.pdf 1969]\n|-\n| [[Second Presbyterian Church (Richmond, Virginia)|Second Presbyterian Church]] (9 North Fifth Street)||1971||[https://web.archive.org/web/20120927040943/http://www.dhr.virginia.gov/registers/Cities/Richmond/127-0016_2nd_Presbyterian_Church_1972_Final_Nomination.pdf 1972]\n|-\n| [[Sixth Mount Zion Baptist Church]] (12\u201314 West Duval Street)||1996||[https://web.archive.org/web/20120927041210/http://www.dhr.virginia.gov/registers/Cities/Richmond/127-0472_Sixth_Mount_Zion_Church_1996_Final_Nomination.pdf 1996]\n|-\n| [[Stonewall Jackson School (Virginia)|Stonewall Jackson School]] (1520 West Main Street)||1984||[https://web.archive.org/web/20120927041455/http://www.dhr.virginia.gov/registers/Cities/Richmond/127-0376_Stonewall_Jackson_School_1984_Final_Nomination.pdf 1984]\n|-\n| Talavera (2315 West Grace Street)||||\n|-\n| [[Wickham House|Valentine Museum and Wickham-Valentine House]] (1005\u20131015 East Clay Street)||1968||[https://web.archive.org/web/20150924011044/http://www.dhr.virginia.gov/registers/Cities/Richmond/127-0020_Wickham-Valentine_House_1969_Final_Nomination.pdf 1969]\n|-\n| [[Virginia House]] (4301 Sulgrave Road)||1989||[https://web.archive.org/web/20091215090058/http://www.dhr.virginia.gov/registers/Cities/Richmond/127-0255_Virginia_House_1990_Final_Nomination.pdf 1990]\n|-\n| [[White House of the Confederacy]] (1200 East Clay Street)||1969||[https://web.archive.org/web/20160505162320/http://www.dhr.virginia.gov/registers/Cities/Richmond/127-0115_WhiteHouseoftheConfederacy_1975_Final_Nomination_NHL.pdf 1966]\n|-\n| [[Wilton House Museum|Wilton]] (215 South Wilton Road)||1975||[https://web.archive.org/web/20120927042507/http://www.dhr.virginia.gov/registers/Cities/Richmond/127-0141_Wilton_1976_Final_Nomination.pdf 1976]\n|-\n| Joseph P. Winston House (103 East Grace Street)||1978||[https://web.archive.org/web/20160304065526/http://www.dhr.virginia.gov/registers/Cities/Richmond/127-0222_Winston,Joseph_P.,House_1979_Final_Nomination.pdf 1979]\n|-\n| [[Woodward House (Richmond, Virginia)|Woodward House-Rockets]] (3017 Williamsburg Avenue)||1974||[https://web.archive.org/web/20120927042608/http://www.dhr.virginia.gov/registers/Cities/Richmond/127-0119_Woodward_House_1974_Final_Nomination.pdf 1974]\n|}\n\n===Food===\nRichmond has been recognized in recent years for being a \"[[foodie]] city\", particularly for its modern renditions of traditional [[cuisine of the Southern United States|Southern cuisine]].<ref name=RTJ_Foodie>{{cite web |url=http://www.richmond.com/food-drink/restaurant-news/article_65a140a2-38ed-11e4-8203-001a4bcf6878.html |title=Richmond One of '8 Under-the-Radar Foodie Cities' in the World |newspaper=Richmond Times-Dispatch |date=September 10, 2014 |author=Karri Peifer |accessdate=July 2, 2015}}</ref><ref name=CNN_foodie>{{cite web |url=http://money.cnn.com/gallery/luxury/2014/12/23/foodie-destinations/7.html |title=Richmond, Virginia \u2013 7 up-and-coming foodie destinations |website=CNN Money |date=January 29, 2015 |author=Steve Hargreaves |accessdate=July 2, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150701211405/http://money.cnn.com/gallery/luxury/2014/12/23/foodie-destinations/7.html |archive-date=July 1, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=USNews_Foodie>{{cite web |url=http://travel.usnews.com/features/8_Under-the-Radar_Foodie_Cities/ |title=8 Under-the-Radar Foodie Cities |newspaper=U.S. News & World Report |date=September 4, 2014 |author=Liz Weiss |accessdate=July 2, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150704073056/http://travel.usnews.com/features/8_Under-the-Radar_Foodie_Cities/ |archive-date=July 4, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> The city also claims the invention of the [[sailor sandwich]], which includes [[pastrami]], [[knockwurst]], [[Swiss cheese (North America)|Swiss cheese]] and [[mustard (condiment)|mustard]] on [[rye bread]].<ref name=\"Imajo\">{{cite news |url=http://www.richmond.com/entertainment/article_9d476505-ada6-56e1-85da-c10c00cbf560.html |title=Richmond's Very Own Sandwich |last=Imajo |first=Anika |date=September 15, 2010 |newspaper=Richmond Times-Dispatch |accessdate=July 2, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170923214640/http://www.richmond.com/entertainment/article_9d476505-ada6-56e1-85da-c10c00cbf560.html |archive-date=September 23, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> Richmond is also where, in 1935, canned beer was made commercially available for the first time.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Maxwell|first=DBS|title=Beer Cans: A Guide for the Archaeologist|journal=Historical Archaeology|year=1993|volume=27|issue=1|pages=95\u2013113|jstor=25616219}}</ref>\n\n==Parks and outdoor recreation==\n[[File:botanicalgarden.jpg|thumb|[[Lewis Ginter Botanical Garden]]]]\n\nThe city operates one of the oldest municipal park systems in the country. The park system began when the city council voted in 1851 to acquire {{convert|7.5|acre|m2}}, now known as [[Monroe Park]]. Today, Monroe Park sits adjacent to the [[Virginia Commonwealth University]] campus and is one of more than 40 parks comprising a total of more than {{convert|1500|acre|ha}}.\n\nSeveral parks are located along the James River, and the James River Parks System offers bike trails, hiking and nature trails, and many scenic overlooks along the river's route through the city.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.trailforks.com/region/james-river-park-system/ | title = James River Park System Mountain Biking Trails | website = Trailforks | access-date = August 26, 2019 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170922002242/https://www.trailforks.com/region/james-river-park-system/ | archive-date = September 22, 2017 | url-status = live }}</ref> The trails are used as part of the Xterra East Championship course for both the running and mountain biking portions of the off-road triathlon.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.richmond.com/news/collection_3ecf827a-1206-11e5-a0d2-5fdcb6ba3682.html|title=XTERRA East Championship|author=Richmond Times-Dispatch|access-date=November 9, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170923213653/http://www.richmond.com/news/collection_3ecf827a-1206-11e5-a0d2-5fdcb6ba3682.html|archive-date=September 23, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThere are also parks on two major islands in the river: [[Belle Isle (Virginia)|Belle Isle]] and Brown's Island. Belle Isle, at various former times a Powhatan fishing village, colonial-era horse race track, and Civil War prison camp, is the larger of the two, and contains many bike trails as well as a small cliff that is used for [[rock climbing]] instruction. One can walk the island and still see many of the remains of the Civil War prison camp, such as an arms storage room and a gun emplacement that was used to quell prisoner riots. Brown's Island is a smaller island and a popular venue of a large number of free outdoor concerts and festivals in the spring and summer, such as the weekly Friday Cheers concert series or the James River Beer and Seafood Festival.\n\n[[File:MaymontPark JapaneseGarden.jpg|thumb|left|Japanese Garden at [[Maymont]]]]\nTwo other major parks in the city along the river are [[Byrd Park]] and [[Maymont]], located near the Fan District. Byrd Park features a {{convert|1|mi|spell=in|adj=on}} running track, with exercise stops, a public [[dog park]], and a number of small lakes for small boats, as well as two monuments, Buddha house, and an amphitheatre. Prominently featured in the park is the [[Carillon|World War I Memorial Carillon]], built in 1926 as a memorial to those that died in the war. Maymont, located adjacent to Byrd Park, is a {{convert|100|acre|ha|adj=on}} [[Victorian architecture|Victorian]] estate with a museum, formal gardens, native wildlife exhibits, nature center, [[carriage]] collection, and children's farm. Other parks in the city include [[Joseph Bryan Park Azalea Garden]], Forest Hill Park (former site of the Forest Hill Amusement Park), [[Chimborazo Park]] (site of the National Battlefield Headquarters), among others.\n\nThe James River itself through Richmond is renowned as one of the best in the country for urban white-water rafting/canoeing/kayaking. Several rafting companies offer complete services. There are also several easily accessed riverside areas within the city limits for rock-hopping, swimming, and picnicking.\n\n[[Lewis Ginter Botanical Garden]] is located adjacent to the city in Henrico County. Founded in 1984, Lewis Ginter Botanical Garden is located on {{convert|80|acre|m2}} and features a glass conservatory, a rose garden, a healing garden, and an accessible-to-all children's garden. The Garden is a public place for the display and scientific study of plants. Lewis Ginter Botanical Garden is one of only two independent public botanical gardens in Virginia and is designated a state botanical garden.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lewisginter.org/about/documents/GardenFactsheetAugust2008.pdf|title=Lewis Ginter Botanical Garden Factsheet|accessdate=November 1, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111012171750/http://www.lewisginter.org/about/documents/GardenFactsheetAugust2008.pdf|archive-date=October 12, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nSeveral [[theme park]]s are also located near the city, including [[Kings Dominion]] to the north, and [[Busch Gardens]] to the east, near [[Williamsburg, Virginia|Williamsburg]].\n\n==Sports==\n{{main|Sports in Richmond, Virginia}}\n\nRichmond is not home to any major league professional sports teams, but since 2013, the [[Washington Redskins]] of the [[National Football League]] have held their [[Training camp (National Football League)|summer training camp]] in the city.<ref name=\"Redskins\">{{cite news|title=Camp Richmond.|url=http://fredericksburg.com/News/FLS/2012/062012/06112012/706390|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130123134627/http://fredericksburg.com/News/FLS/2012/062012/06112012/706390|url-status=dead|archive-date=January 23, 2013|accessdate=July 10, 2012|website=Fredericksburg.com|date=June 11, 2012}}</ref> There are also several [[minor league]] sports in the city, including the [[Richmond Kickers]] of the [[United Soccer League]] (second tier of [[American soccer pyramid|American soccer]]) and the [[Richmond Flying Squirrels]] of the Class AA [[Eastern League (baseball)|Eastern League]] of [[Minor League Baseball]] (an affiliate of the [[San Francisco Giants]]).<ref name=\"kickers\">{{cite web|title=About Richmond Kickers.|url=http://www.uslsoccer.com/teams/2012/22375.html#ABOUT|publisher=USL Soccer|accessdate=July 10, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120715131430/http://www.uslsoccer.com/teams/2012/22375.html#ABOUT|archivedate=July 15, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"squirrels\">{{cite web|title=Richmond Flying Squirrels.|url=http://www.milb.com/index.jsp?sid=t3410|publisher=[[Minor League Baseball]]|accessdate=July 10, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120710122446/http://www.milb.com/index.jsp?sid=t3410|archive-date=July 10, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> The Kickers began playing in Richmond in 1993, and currently play at [[City Stadium (Richmond)|City Stadium]]. In 2018 the Richmond Kickers left the USL to become founders in Division 3 Soccer. The Squirrels opened their first season at [[The Diamond (Richmond, Virginia)|The Diamond]] on April 15, 2010.<ref>{{cite news|last=O'Connor|first=John|title=Flying Squirrels picked as new baseball team name.|url=http://www2.timesdispatch.com/sports/2009/oct/15/flying_squirrels_picked_as_new_baseball_team_xml_n-ar-22754/|accessdate=July 10, 2012|newspaper=[[Richmond Times Dispatch]]|date=October 15, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130204102201/http://www2.timesdispatch.com/sports/2009/oct/15/flying_squirrels_picked_as_new_baseball_team_xml_n-ar-22754/|archivedate=February 4, 2013}}</ref> From 1966 through 2008, the city was home to the [[Richmond Braves]], a AAA affiliate of the [[Atlanta Braves]] of [[Major League Baseball]], until the franchise relocated to [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]].<ref>{{cite news|authors=Ress, David; Martz, Michael|title=Braves strike out... for new home in Ga.|newspaper=[[Richmond Times Dispatch]]|date=January 16, 2008}}</ref>\n\nIt is also the home to the [[Richmond Black Widows]], the city's first women's football team, founded in 2015 by [[Sarah Schkeeper]]. They are a part of the [[Women's Football Alliance]]. Their game season begins in April, with preseason beginning in January.\n\nAnother significant sports venue is the 6,000-seat [[Arthur Ashe Athletic Center]], a multi-purpose arena named for tennis great and Richmond resident [[Arthur Ashe]]. This facility hosts a variety of local sporting events, concerts, and other activities. As the home of Arthur Ashe, the sport of [[tennis]] is also popular in Richmond, and in 2010, the [[United States Tennis Association]] named Richmond as the third \"Best Tennis Town\", behind [[Charleston, South Carolina]], and [[Atlanta, Georgia]].<ref name=\"USTA\">{{cite news|title=Richmond Places Third in Best Tennis Town.|url=http://www.midatlantic.usta.com/richmond_places_3rd_in_best_tennis_town/|accessdate=July 10, 2012|newspaper=[[United States Tennis Association]]|date=September 7, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130605075238/http://www.midatlantic.usta.com/richmond_places_3rd_in_best_tennis_town/|archive-date=June 5, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nAuto racing is also popular in the area. The [[Richmond Raceway]] (RR) has hosted [[Monster Energy]] [[NASCAR]] [[Monster Energy NASCAR Cup Series|Cup]] races since 1953, as well as the Capital City 400 from 1962 \u2212 1980.<ref name=\"RIR\">{{cite web|title=Virginia is for Lovers and Richmond International Raceway team up for NASCAR Spring Cup Series Race.|url=http://www.rir.com/Articles/2012/04/CC400-Announcement.aspx|publisher=[[Richmond International Raceway]]|accessdate=July 10, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140521201753/http://www.rir.com/Articles/2012/04/CC400-Announcement.aspx|archive-date=May 21, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> RIR also hosted IndyCar's Suntrust Indy Challenge from 2001 \u2212 2009. Another track, [[Southside Speedway]], has operated since 1959 and sits just southwest of Richmond in [[Chesterfield County, Virginia|Chesterfield County]]. This {{convert|.333|mi|km|adj=on}} oval short-track has become known as the \"Toughest Track in the South\" and \"The Action Track\", and features weekly stock car racing on Friday nights.<ref name=\"Southside_Speedway\">{{cite web|title=Southside Speedway Track Facts.|url=http://southsidespeedway.com/aboutus.html|publisher=[[Southside Speedway]]|accessdate=July 10, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120427105227/http://www.southsidespeedway.com/aboutus.html|archivedate=April 27, 2012}}</ref> Southside Speedway has acted as the breeding grounds for many past NASCAR legends including [[Richard Petty]], [[Bobby Allison]] and [[Darrell Waltrip]], and claims to be the home track of NASCAR superstar [[Denny Hamlin]].<ref name=\"Netherland_Tom\">{{cite news|last=Netherland|first=Tom|title=Richmond Loves Racing.|url=http://www.richmondmagazine.com/?articleID=418d39f6e212efeaa4d223d19cd7d643|accessdate=July 10, 2012|newspaper=Richmond Magazine|date=February 2006|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141218203422/http://richmondmagazine.com/?articleID=418d39f6e212efeaa4d223d19cd7d643|archive-date=December 18, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Brockwell_Kent\">{{cite news|last=Brockwell|first=Kent Jennings|title=10 Questions: Sue Clements: Southside Speedway's co-owner/promoter.|url=http://southsidespeedway.com/sueclements2006.html|accessdate=July 10, 2012|website=Richmond.com|date=September 4, 2006|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130603012914/http://southsidespeedway.com/sueclements2006.html|archivedate=June 3, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Richmond hosted the [[2015 UCI Road World Championships]], which had cyclists from 76 countries and an economic impact on the [[Greater Richmond Region]] estimated to be $158.1 million, from both event staging and visitor spending.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://richmond2015.com/ |title=Richmond 2015 |publisher=Richmond 2015 |date=September 17, 2015 |accessdate=November 12, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151111223701/http://richmond2015.com/ |archive-date=November 11, 2015 |url-status=live }</ref>. The course used for the championships was the first real-world location to be recreated within the indoor cycle training application, [[Zwift]], and has been subsequently joined within the game by the UCI world championships courses from 2018 ([[Innsbruck]]) and 2019 ([[Harrogate]]).\n\n[[College basketball]] has also had recent success with the [[Richmond Spiders]] and the [[VCU Rams]], both of the [[Atlantic 10 Conference]]. The Spiders' men's and women's teams play at [[Robins Center]] and the Rams' men's and women's teams play at the [[Stuart C. Siegel Center]].\n\n==Media==\n{{more citations needed|date=September 2016}}\n{{Main|Media in Richmond, Virginia}}\nThe ''[[Richmond Times-Dispatch]]'', the local daily newspaper in Richmond with a Sunday circulation of 120,000, is owned by BH Media, a subsidiary of Warren Buffett's [[Berkshire Hathaway]] company.  ''[[Style Weekly]]'' is a standard weekly publication covering popular culture, arts, and entertainment, owned by Landmark Communications. [[RVA Magazine]] is the city's only independent art music and culture publication, was once monthly, but is now issued quarterly. The ''[[Richmond Free Press]]'' and the ''Voice'' cover the news from an African-American perspective.\n\nThe Richmond metro area is served by many local television and radio stations. {{As of|2010}}, the Richmond-Petersburg [[designated market area]] (DMA) is the 58th largest in the U.S. with 553,950 homes according to Nielsen Market Research.<ref name=\"nielsen\">{{cite web|author=Holmes, Gary |url=http://en-us.nielsen.com/etc/content/nielsen_dotcom/en_us/home/measurement/tv_research.mbt.39577.RelatedLinks.13293.MediaPath.pdf |work=[[Nielsen Media Research]] |title=Local Television Market Universe Estimates |accessdate=October 2, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090711082126/http://en-us.nielsen.com/etc/content/nielsen_dotcom/en_us/home/measurement/tv_research.mbt.39577.RelatedLinks.13293.MediaPath.pdf |archivedate=July 11, 2009 }}</ref> The major network television affiliates are [[WTVR-TV]] 6 ([[Columbia Broadcasting System|CBS]]), [[WRIC-TV]] 8 ([[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]), [[WWBT]] 12 ([[NBC]]), [[WRLH-TV]] 35 ([[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]), and [[WUPV]] 65 ([[The CW Television Network|CW]]). [[Public Broadcasting Service]] stations include [[WCVE-TV]] 23 and [[WCVW]] 57. There are also a wide variety of radio stations in the Richmond area, catering to many different interests, including news, [[talk radio]], and sports, as well as an eclectic mix of musical interests.  Richmond enjoys a [[Low-power broadcasting#United States|low power FM Station]], [[WRIR]], which features all volunteer community supported radio at all hours.\n\n==Government and politics==\n[[File:Richmond City Hall (2988924475).jpg|thumb|Richmond City Hall]]\n{{more citations needed|section|date=June 2014}}\n{{See also|List of mayors of Richmond, Virginia}}\n{{main|Government of Richmond, Virginia}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  style=\"margin:auto; float:right; font-size:95%;\"\n|+ '''Presidential Elections Results'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://uselectionatlas.org/RESULTS/|title=Dave Leip's Atlas of U.S. Presidential Elections|website=uselectionatlas.org|access-date=August 26, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110222105145/http://uselectionatlas.org/RESULTS/|archive-date=February 22, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|- style=\"background:lightgrey;\"\n! Year\n! [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n! [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n! [[Third Party (United States)|Third Parties]]\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[United States presidential election in Virginia, 2016|2016]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|15.1% ''15,581''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''78.6%''' ''81,259''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|6.4% ''6,566''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[United States presidential election in Virginia, 2012|2012]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|20.6% ''20,050''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''77.8%''' ''75,921''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|1.6% ''1,598''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[United States presidential election in Virginia, 2008|2008]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|20.0% ''18,649''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''79.1%''' ''73,623''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|0.9% ''813''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[United States presidential election in Virginia, 2004|2004]]'''\n|  style=