19.4% ''2,600''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''73.8%''' ''9,904''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|6.8% ''917''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[United States presidential election in Virginia, 1920|1920]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|23.0% ''4,515''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''75.9%''' ''14,878''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|1.0% ''202''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[United States presidential election in Virginia, 1916|1916]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|14.6% ''1,210''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''84.2%''' ''6,987''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|1.3% ''106''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[United States presidential election in Virginia, 1912|1912]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|6.1% ''405''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''85.0%''' ''5,632''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|8.9% ''586''\n|}\n\nRichmond city government consists of a [[city council]] with representatives from nine districts serving in a [[legislative]] and oversight capacity, as well as a popularly elected, at-large mayor serving as head of the [[executive branch]]. Citizens in each of the nine districts elect one council representative each to serve a four-year term. Beginning with the November 2008 election Council terms was lengthened to 4 years. The city council elects from among its members one member to serve as Council President and one to serve as Council Vice President. The city council meets at City Hall, located at 900 E. Broad St., 2nd Floor, on the second and fourth Mondays of every month, except August.\n\nIn 1977, a federal district court ruled in favor of [[Curtis Holt Jr.]] who had claimed the council's existing election process&nbsp;\u2014 an at large voting system&nbsp;\u2014 was racially biased. The verdict required the city to rebuild its council into nine distinct wards. Within the year the city council switched from majority white to majority black, reflecting the city's populace. This new city council elected Richmond's first black mayor, [[Henry L. Marsh]].\n\nIn 1990 religion and politics intersected to impact the outcome of the Eighth District election in South Richmond. With the endorsements of black power brokers, black clergy and the Richmond Crusade for Voters, South Richmond residents made history, electing Reverend A. Carl Prince to the Richmond City Council. As the first African American Baptist Minister elected to the Richmond City Council, Prince's election paved the way for a political paradigm shift in politics that persist today. Following Prince's election, Reverend Gwendolyn Hedgepeth and the Reverend Leonidas Young, former Richmond Mayor were elected to public office. Prior to Prince's election black clergy made political endorsements and served as appointees to the Richmond School Board and other boards throughout the city. Today religion and politics continues to thrive in the Commonwealth of Virginia. Dwight C. Jones, a prominent Baptist pastor and former Chairman of the Richmond School Board and Member of the Virginia House of Delegates serves as Mayor of the City of Richmond.\n\nRichmond's government changed in 2004 from a [[council-manager]] form of government to an at-large, popularly elected Mayor. In a landslide election, incumbent mayor Rudy McCollum was defeated by [[L. Douglas Wilder]], who previously served Virginia as the first elected African American governor in the United States since [[Reconstruction era of the United States|Reconstruction]]. The current mayor of Richmond is [[Levar Stoney]] who was elected in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|title=Richmond City Government|url=http://www.richmondgov.com/Mayor/index.aspx|accessdate=January 30, 2017|ref=Richmond City Site|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170129072427/http://www.richmondgov.com/Mayor/index.aspx|archive-date=January 29, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The mayor is not a part of the Richmond City Council.\n\n{{As of|2017|df=US}}, the Richmond City Council consisted of:\n* Chris A. Hilbert, 3rd District (Northside), President of Council\n* Cynthia I Newbille, 7th District (East End) Vice-President of Council\n* Andreas D. Addison, 1st District (West End)\n* Kimberly B. Gray, 2nd District (North Central)\n* Kristen Nye Larson, 4th District (Southwest)\n* Parker C. Agelasto, 5th District (Central)\n* Ellen F. Robertson, 6th District (Gateway)\n* Reva M. Trammell, 8th District (Southside)\n* Michael J. Jones 9th District (South Central)\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.richmondgov.com/CityCouncil/contacts.aspx|title=Richmond VA > City Council > Contacts|work=richmondgov.com|access-date=June 1, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140716195941/http://www.richmondgov.com/CityCouncil/contacts.aspx|archive-date=July 16, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\n[[File:Tjhs.jpg|thumb|The [[Art Deco]]-styled Thomas Jefferson High School in the near West End]]\n\n===Public schools===\n{{Main|Richmond Public Schools}}\nThe city of Richmond operates 28 elementary schools, nine [[middle school]]s, and eight high schools, serving a total student population of 24,000 students.<ref name=\"rps_facts\">{{cite web|url=http://www.richmond.k12.va.us/indexnew/sub/fastfacts.cfm|title=Richmond Public Schools Overview \u2013 At A Glance.|date=June 2008|publisher=[[Richmond Public Schools]]|accessdate=October 2, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090831051847/http://www.richmond.k12.va.us/indexnew/sub/fastfacts.cfm|archive-date=August 31, 2009|url-status=live}}</ref> There is one Governor's School in the city \u2212 the [[Maggie L. Walker Governor's School for Government and International Studies]]. In 2008, it was named as one of [[Newsweek]] magazine's 18 \"public elite\" high schools,<ref name=\"Hickey_Gordon\">{{cite news|last=Hickey|first=Gordon|title=Governor Kaine Congratulates Thomas Jefferson High School For Science And Technology ~ Fairfax County school again tops U.S. News & World Report's list of 100 best ~|url=http://www.doe.virginia.gov/news/news_releases/2008/dec08.shtml|accessdate=July 10, 2012|newspaper=Virginia Department of Education|date=December 8, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120926180907/http://www.doe.virginia.gov/news/news_releases/2008/dec08.shtml|archive-date=September 26, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> and in 2012, it was rated #16 of America's best high schools overall.<ref name=\"Newsweek_2012\">{{cite news|title=America's Best High Schools 2012. |url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/newsweek/2012/05/20/america-s-best-high-schools.html |accessdate=July 10, 2012 |newspaper=[[Newsweek]] |date=May 20, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120521045950/http://www.thedailybeast.com/newsweek/2012/05/20/america-s-best-high-schools.html |archivedate=May 21, 2012 }}</ref> Richmond's public school district also runs one of Virginia's four public [[charter school]]s, the Patrick Henry School of Science and Arts, which was founded in 2010.<ref name=\"charter_schools\">{{cite web|title=Virginia's Public Charter Schools.|url=http://www.doe.virginia.gov/instruction/charter_schools/charter_schools.shtml|publisher=Virginia Department of Education|accessdate=July 10, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120926202734/http://www.doe.virginia.gov/instruction/charter_schools/charter_schools.shtml|archive-date=September 26, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Private schools===\nAs of 2008, there were 36 private schools serving grades one or higher in the city of Richmond.<ref name=\"private_schools_list\">{{cite news|title=Private Schools List.|url=http://www2.timesdispatch.com/special_section/2008/jan/27/private_schools_list-ar-138084/|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130204083729/http://www2.timesdispatch.com/special_section/2008/jan/27/private_schools_list-ar-138084/|url-status=dead|archive-date=February 4, 2013|accessdate=July 10, 2012|newspaper=[[Richmond Times Dispatch]]|date=January 27, 2008}}</ref> Some of these schools include: Banner Christian School, [[Benedictine College Preparatory]], St. Bridget School, [[Brook Road Academy]], [[Collegiate School (Richmond, Virginia)|Collegiate School]], Grace Christian School, Grove Christian School, Guardian Christian Academy, [[St. Christopher's School, Richmond|St. Christopher's School]], [[Saint Gertrude High School|St. Gertrude High School]], [[St. Catherine's School, Richmond, Virginia|St. Catherine's School]], [[Southside Baptist Christian School]], [[Northstar Academy (Richmond, Virginia)|Northstar Academy]], [[The Steward School]], [[Trinity Episcopal High School|Trinity Episcopal School]], The New Community School, and Veritas School.\n\n===Colleges and universities===\nThe Richmond area has many major institutions of higher education, including [[Virginia Commonwealth University]] (public), [[University of Richmond]] (private), [[Virginia Union University]] (private), [[Virginia College]] (private), [[South University]]\u2013Richmond (private, for-profit), [[Union Theological Seminary & Presbyterian School of Christian Education]] (private), and the Baptist Theological Seminary in Richmond (BTSR\u2014private). Several community colleges are found in the metro area, including [[J. Sargeant Reynolds Community College]] and [[John Tyler Community College]] ([[Chesterfield County, Virginia|Chesterfield County]]). In addition, there are several Technical Colleges in Richmond including ITT Technical Institute, [[ECPI College of Technology]] and Centura College. There are several vocational colleges also, such as Fortis College and Bryant Stratton College.\n\n[[Virginia State University]] is located about {{convert|20|mi|km}} south of Richmond, in the suburb of [[Ettrick, Virginia|Ettrick]], just outside [[Petersburg, Virginia|Petersburg]]. [[Randolph-Macon College]] is located about {{convert|15|mi|km}} north of Richmond, in the incorporated town of [[Ashland, Virginia|Ashland]].\n\n==Infrastructure==\n\n===Transportation===\n[[File:Main Street Station.jpg|thumb|Richmond's downtown [[Main Street Station (Richmond)|Main Street Station]]]]\n{{Main|Transportation in Richmond, Virginia}}\nThe Greater Richmond area is served by the [[Richmond International Airport]] {{airport codes|RIC|KRIC}}, located in nearby [[Sandston, Virginia|Sandston]], {{convert|7|mi|km|spell=in}} southeast of Richmond and within an hour drive of historic [[Williamsburg, Virginia]]. Richmond International is now served by nine airlines with over 200 daily flights providing non-stop service to major destination markets and connecting flights to destinations worldwide. A record 3.3 million passengers used Richmond International Airport in 2006, a 13% increase over 2005.\n\nRichmond is a major hub for intercity [[bus]] company [[Greyhound Lines]], with its terminal at 2910 N Boulevard. Multiple runs per day connect directly with Washington, D.C., New York, Raleigh, and elsewhere. Direct trips to New York take approximately 7.5 hours. Discount carrier [[Megabus (North America)|Megabus]] also provides curbside service from outside of Main Street Station. Direct service is available to Washington, D.C., [[Hampton Roads]], [[Charlotte]], [[Raleigh, North Carolina|Raleigh]], [[Baltimore]], and [[Philadelphia]]. Most other connections to Megabus served cities, such as New York, can be made from Washington, D.C.<ref>{{cite web |last=Garbarek |first=Ben |url=http://www.nbc12.com/Global/story.asp?S=13514197 |title=Megabus coming to Richmond with cheap fares \u2013 NBC12 News, Weather Sports, Traffic, and Programming Guide for Richmond, VA &#124; |publisher=Nbc12.com |date=November 16, 2010 |accessdate=November 1, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120307090949/http://www.nbc12.com/Global/story.asp?S=13514197 |archive-date=March 7, 2012 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n\nLocal [[transit (transportation)|transit]] and [[paratransit]] bus service in Richmond, [[Henrico County, Virginia|Henrico]], and [[Chesterfield County, Virginia|Chesterfield]] counties is provided by the [[Greater Richmond Transit of Richmond, Virginia|Greater Richmond Transit Company]] (GRTC). The GRTC, however, serves only small parts of the suburban counties. The far West End (Innsbrook and Short Pump) and almost all of Chesterfield County have no public transportation despite dense housing, retail, and office development. According to a 2008 GRTC operations analysis report, a majority of GRTC riders utilize their services because they do not have an available alternative such as a private vehicle.<ref name=\"GRTC rider stats\">{{cite news|title=Comprehensive Operations Analysis Final Report |url=http://www.ridegrtc.com/images/GRTC%20COA%20ExecSummary.pdf |accessdate=June 16, 2010 |newspaper=[[Greater Richmond Transit Company]] |date=March 3, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100415054519/http://www.ridegrtc.com/images/GRTC%20COA%20ExecSummary.pdf |archivedate=April 15, 2010 }}</ref> Richmond, and the surrounding metropolitan area, was granted a roughly $25 million grant from the U.S. Department of Transportation in 2014<ref>{{cite web|title=U.S. Transportation Secretary Foxx Announces $24.9 Million in TIGER Funds for Richmond Bus Rapid Transit|url=https://www.transportation.gov/briefing-room/us-transportation-secretary-foxx-announces-249-million-tiger-funds-richmond-bus-rapid|website=US Department of Transportation|accessdate=September 14, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161004001259/https://www.transportation.gov/briefing-room/us-transportation-secretary-foxx-announces-249-million-tiger-funds-richmond-bus-rapid|archive-date=October 4, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> to support the [[GRTC Pulse]] [[bus rapid transit]] system, which will run along Broad Street from Willow Lawn to {{not a typo|Rocketts}} Landing, in the first phase of an improved public transportation hub for the region.\n\nThe Richmond area also has two railroad stations served by [[Amtrak]]. Each station receives regular service from north of Richmond including Washington, D.C., Philadelphia, and New York. The suburban [[Richmond Staples Mill Road (Amtrak station)|Staples Mill Road Station]] is located on a major north-south freight line and receives all service to and from all points south including, [[Raleigh, North Carolina|Raleigh]], [[Durham, North Carolina|Durham]], [[Savannah, Georgia|Savannah]], [[Newport News, Virginia|Newport News]], [[Williamsburg, Virginia|Williamsburg]] and Florida. Richmond's only railway station located within the city limits, the historic [[Main Street Station (Richmond)|Main Street Station]], was renovated in 2004.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rmaonline.org/mainst/mainsthistory.html |title=The History of Main Street Station (RMA) |publisher=Rmaonline.org |accessdate=November 1, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111101114102/http://www.rmaonline.org/mainst/mainsthistory.html |archivedate=November 1, 2011  }}</ref> As of 2010, the station only receives trains headed to and from [[Newport News, Virginia|Newport News]] and [[Williamsburg, Virginia|Williamsburg]] due to track layout. As a result, the Staples Mill Road station receives more trains and serves more passengers overall.\n\nRichmond also benefits from an excellent position in reference to the state's transportation network, lying at the junction of east-west [[Interstate 64]] and north-south [[Interstate 95 in Virginia|Interstate 95]], two of the most heavily traveled highways in the state, as well as along several major rail lines.\n\n===Major highways===\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* {{Jct|state=VA|I|64}}\n* {{Jct|state=VA|I|95|name1=[[Richmond\u2013Petersburg Turnpike]]}}\n* {{Jct|state=VA|I|195}} (toll route)\n* {{Jct|state=VA|I|295}}\n* {{Jct|state=VA|US|1}}\n* {{Jct|state=VA|US|33}}\n* {{Jct|state=VA|US|60}}\n* {{Jct|state=VA|US|250}} ([[Broad Street (Richmond, Virginia)|Broad Street]])\n* {{Jct|state=VA|US|301}}\n* {{Jct|state=VA|US|360}} (Hull St Rd; Hull St; N 14th St; joins US 60 Main St;  WB 17th St [Oliver Hill Way], EB W 18th St; Mechanicsville Tnpk)\n* {{Jct|state=VA|SR|5}} (E Main St; N 25th St)\n* {{Jct|state=VA|SR|6}}\n* {{Jct|state=VA|SR|10}} (Broad Rock Blvd)\n* {{Jct|state=VA|SR|33}}\n* {{Jct|state=VA|SR|76|name1=[[Powhite Parkway]] toll route}}\n* {{Jct|state=VA|SR|146}}\n* {{Jct|state=VA|SR|147}}\n* {{Jct|state=VA|SR|150|name1=[[Chippenham Parkway]]}}\n* {{Jct|state=VA|SR|161}}\n* {{Jct|state=VA|SR|195}} (toll route)\n* {{Jct|state=VA|SR|197}}\n* {{Jct|state=VA|SR|288}}\n* {{Jct|state=VA|SR|353}}\n* {{Jct|state=VA|SR|895|name1=[[Pocohontas Parkway]] toll route}}\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Utilities===\n[[Electric power|Electricity]] in the Richmond Metro area is provided by [[Dominion Energy]]. The company, based in Richmond, is one of the nation's largest producers of energy, serving retail energy customers in nine states. Electricity is provided in the Richmond area primarily by the [[North Anna Nuclear Generating Station]] and [[Surry Nuclear Generating Station]], as well as a coal-fired station in [[Chester, Virginia]]. These three plants provide a total of 4,453 [[megawatts]] of power. Several other natural gas plants provide extra power during times of peak demand. These include facilities in [[Chester, Virginia|Chester]], and [[Surry, Virginia|Surry]], and two plants in Richmond (Gravel Neck and Darbytown).<ref>[https://www.dominionenergy.com/ Dominion Energy] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171020185037/https://www.dominionenergy.com/ |date=October 20, 2017 }}.</ref>\n\nNatural gas in the Richmond Metro area is provided by the city's Department of Public Utilities and also serves portions of [[Henrico County, Virginia|Henrico]] and [[Chesterfield County, Virginia|Chesterfield]] counties.\n\nWater is provided by the city's Department of Public Utilities, and is one of the largest water producers in Virginia, with a modern plant that can treat up to 132 million gallons of water a day from the [[James River (Virginia)|James River]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.richmondgov.com/|title=Richmond, VA|work=richmondgov.com|access-date=May 24, 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120103103032/http://www.richmondgov.com/|archive-date=January 3, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> The facility also provides water to the surrounding area through wholesale contracts with [[Henrico County, Virginia|Henrico]], [[Chesterfield County, Virginia|Chesterfield]], and [[Hanover County, Virginia|Hanover]] counties. Overall, this results in a facility that provides water for approximately 500,000 people.\n\nThe [[wastewater]] treatment plant and distribution system of water mains, pumping stations and storage facilities provide water to approximately 62,000 customers in the city. There is also a wastewater treatment plant located on the south bank of the James River. This plant can treat up to 70 million gallons of water per day of sanitary sewage and stormwater before returning it to the river. The wastewater utility also operates and maintains {{convert|1500|mi|km}} of sanitary sewer and pumping stations, {{convert|38|mi|km}} of intercepting sewer lines, and the Shockoe Retention Basin, a 44-million-gallon stormwater reservoir used during heavy rains.\n\n==International relations==\n\n===Sister cities===\nRichmond maintains the following six [[town twinning|sister city]] relationships:<ref name=RVA_sistercities>{{cite web |url=http://www.richmondgov.com/content/CommissionSisterCities/index.aspx |title=Richmond Sister Cities Commission |publisher=Richmond, Virginia Government |accessdate=May 12, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304000743/http://www.richmondgov.com/content/CommissionSisterCities/index.aspx |archive-date=March 4, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* [[Richmond upon Thames]], [[London]], United Kingdom\n* [[Olsztyn]], Poland\n* [[Saitama, Saitama|Saitama]], Japan\n* [[S\u00e9gou]], Mali\n* [[Windhoek]], Namibia\n* [[Zhengzhou]], China\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Virginia}}\n* [[:Category:People from Richmond, Virginia|List of Richmonders]]\n* [[National Register of Historic Places listings in Richmond, Virginia]]\n* [[Richmond Police Department (Virginia)|Richmond Police Department]]\n* [[Culture of Virginia]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Bill, Alfred Hoyt. ''The Beleaguered City: Richmond, 1861\u20131865'' (1946).\n* Calcutt, Rebecca Barbour. ''Richmond's Wartime Hospitals'' (Pelican Publishing, 2005).\n* Chesson, Michael B. ''Richmond after the war, 1865\u20131890'' (Virginia State Library, 1981).\n* {{cite book| last=Dabney | first=Virginius | authorlink= Virginius Dabney| title=Richmond: The Story of a City| year=1990 | edition= revised and expanded |isbn=978-0813912745|  publisher= [[University Press of Virginia]]}}\n* Furgurson, Ernest B. ''Ashes of glory: Richmond at war'' (1996).\n* Hoffman, Steven J. ''Race, Class and Power in the Building of Richmond, 1870-1920'' (McFarland, 2004).\n* Mustian, Thomas F. ''Facts and Legends of Richmond Area Streets.'' (Richmond, VA: Dementi Milestone Publishing, 2007).\n* Thomas, Emory M. ''The Confederate State of Richmond: A Biography of the Capital'' (LSU Press, 1998).\n* Trammell, Jack. ''The Richmond Slave Trade: The Economic Backbone of the Old Dominion'' (The History Press, 2012).\n* Wright, Mike. ''City Under Siege: Richmond in the Civil War'' (Rowman & Littlefield, 1995)\n\n==External links==\n{{Sister project links|Richmond, Virginia|voy=Richmond}}\n* {{official website|http://www.richmondgov.com/}}\n* [https://www.chamberrva.com/ ChamberRVA], the regional chamber of commerce for Greater Richmond\n* [http://www.visitrichmondva.com/ Richmond Metropolitan Convention & Visitors Bureau]\n* [http://www.richmondcenter.com/ Greater Richmond Convention Center]\n* [http://www.nps.gov/history/nr/travel/richmond/index.html Richmond, Virginia], a National Park Service ''Discover Our Shared Heritage'' travel itinerary\n* {{YouTube|E4Id5ZwtMRk|video:Exploring the James River Parks of Richmond}}\n* [http://www.richmondlions.com/ Richmond Lions Rugby Football Club Website]\n\n{{Geographic location\n|Centre    = Richmond, Virginia\n|North     = [[Henrico County, Virginia|Henrico County]]\n|Northeast =\n|East      = [[Henrico County, Virginia|Henrico County]]\n|Southeast =\n|South     = [[Chesterfield County, Virginia|Chesterfield County]]\n|Southwest =\n|West      = [[Henrico County, Virginia|Henrico County]]\n|Northwest = }}\n{{Greater Richmond Region}}\n{{Richmond, Virginia neighborhoods}}\n{{Virginia}}\n{{US state capitals}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Coord|37|32|N|77|28|W|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Richmond, Virginia]]\n[[Category:Cities in Virginia]]\n[[Category:Greater Richmond Region]]\n[[Category:Populated places on the James River (Virginia)]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1737]]\n[[Category:1737 establishments in the Thirteen Colonies]]\n[[Category:Capitals of former nations]]\n", "name_user": "Mattchoochoo33", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTransportation:The original sentence is incorrect. There is an existing public transit route 19 that goes to Short Pump and the far West End as of 2018. Sources https://www.richmond.com/news/local/grtc-route-updates-including-service-to-short-pump-to-take-effect-sept-16/article_d25759bf-2303-5bc1-a66a-1ca2b7270f6c.html http://ridegrtc.com/grtc-service-enhancements-in-henrico-county https://wtvr.com/2018/08/30/grtc-henrico-expansion-includes-route-to-short-pump-begins-sept-16/", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Richmond,_Virginia"}
{"title_page": "The Strat (Las Vegas)", "text_new": "{{short description|Hotel in Las Vegas}}\n{{Infobox building\n|name = The Strat Hotel, Casino and SkyPod\n|logo = Logo for The Strat hotel-casino.jpg\n|logo_caption = \n|image = Aerial view Casino Stratosphere LAS 09 2017 4912.jpg\n|caption = Stratosphere Tower in 2017\n|altitude =\n|cost={{US$|70 million}}\n|groundbreaking_date = November 5, 1991\n|start_date = February 1992\n|completion_date = \n|opened_date = April 30, 1996<ref name=\"STRAT emp\">{{cite web |url=https://www.emporis.com/buildings/122231/stratosphere-tower-las-vegas-nv-usa |title=Stratosphere Tower, Las Vegas |publisher=Emporis |accessdate=2017-01-15}}</ref><ref name=USA>{{citeweb |url=http://traveltips.usatoday.com/stratosphere-tower-3146.html |title=Facts about the Stratosphere Tower|publisher=USA Today |accessdate=2017-01-16}}</ref> \n|floor_area = \n|address = 2000 [[Las Vegas Boulevard]] South\n|location = [[Las Vegas]], [[Nevada]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n|room_count=\n|building_type = [[Observation tower]]\n|coordinates = {{Coord|36.147386|-115.155389|region:US-NV_type:landmark|display=inline,title}}\n|antenna_spire = {{Convert|1149|ft|1|abbr=on}}\n|floor_count = \n|status = Operating\n|est_completion = \n|architect = Ned Baldwin\n|developer = [[Bob Stupak]]\n|elevator_count = 7 (4 high speed double deck elevators, 3 local elevators in the pod)\n|main_contractor = \n|architecture_firm = \n|structural_engineer = \n|services_engineer = \n|civil_engineer = \n|url = \n|references = \n|module={{Infobox casino\n|embed=yes\n|name        = Other information\n|mapframe=no\n|rooms       = 2,427\n|theme =\n|date_opened = \n|space_gaming= {{convert|80000|sqft|abbr=on}}\n|attractions = {{hlist|[[Big Shot (ride)|Big Shot]]|[[Insanity (ride)|Insanity]]|[[X-Scream]]|Stratosphere Tower|[[SkyJump Las Vegas]]}}\n|shows       = \n|notable_restaurants = {{hlist|Top of the World|Fellini's Ristorante|Roxy's Diner|Lucky's}}\n|owner       = [[Golden Entertainment]]\n|casino_type = Land-based\n|renovations = 2000\u201301, 2010,<ref name=20-million>{{cite web |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/2011/jan/13/stratosphere-undergoes-20-million-renovation/ |title=Stratosphere undergoes $20 million renovation |publisher=Las Vegas Sun |accessdate=2017-01-15}}</ref> 2019\u20132020\n|names_pre   = Stratosphere\n|coordinates = \n|website     = {{URL|thestrat.com}}\n}}}}\n'''The Strat Hotel, Casino and SkyPod'''{{efn|Stylized as \"The STRAT\".<ref name=\"Press\" />}} (formerly the '''Stratosphere''') is a [[hotel]], [[casino]] and [[tower]] located on [[Las Vegas Boulevard]] just north of the [[Las Vegas Strip]] in [[Las Vegas]], [[Nevada]], United States. The Strat is owned and operated by [[Golden Entertainment]], which acquired the resort and three other properties from [[American Casino & Entertainment Properties]] for $850 million in 2017.<ref name=\"reviewjournal.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/business/casinos-gaming/golden-closes-on-850m-deal-for-stratosphere-3-other-casinos/|title=Golden closes on $850M deal for Stratosphere, 3 other casinos|date=23 October 2017|work=Las Vegas Review-Journal|accessdate=31 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe property's signature attraction is the {{convert|1149|ft|1|abbr=on}} Stratosphere Tower, the tallest [[List of tallest towers in the world|freestanding observation tower]] in the United States,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stratospherehotel.com/thrills/|title=- Big Shot Stratosphere Tower Rides|author=|year=2011|publisher=Las Vegas Amusement Parks|accessdate=12 January 2011}}</ref> and the second-tallest in the [[Western Hemisphere]], surpassed only by the [[CN Tower]] in [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]]. It is the tallest tower west of the Mississippi River<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stratospherehotel.com/content/download/587/4973/version/1/file/Dale_Tower.pdf|title=The Stratosphere Tower to Dim Lights in Honor of Seven-Time NASCAR Champion Dale Earnhardt|website=Stratospherehotel.com|format=PDF|accessdate=2016-03-12}}</ref> and also the [[List of tallest buildings in Las Vegas|tallest structure in Las Vegas]] and [[List of tallest buildings in Nevada|in the state of Nevada]].<ref name=\"STRAT emp\" /> The hotel is a separate building with 24 stories, 2,427 rooms and an {{convert|80000|sqft|abbr=on}} casino. The Strat is located within the city limits of Las Vegas, and is sometimes considered to be the northernmost resort on the Las Vegas Strip, which is not located within the city.<ref name=\"North\" /><ref name=\"Kat2019\">{{cite news|url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/entertainment/entertainment-columns/kats/the-new-strat-still-says-were-part-of-the-las-vegas-strip-1696101/|title=The new Strat still says, 'We're part of the Las Vegas Strip'|last=Katsilometes|first=John|date=2019-06-26|work=Las Vegas Review-Journal|accessdate=2019-07-26}}</ref>\n\nThe Stratosphere, a project by [[Bob Stupak]], began construction in 1991.<ref name=\"Breaks\" /> The project integrated portions of the former [[Vegas World]] hotel-casino, which Stupak opened on the site in 1979. The Stratosphere opened on April 30, 1996.<ref name=\"Rave\" /> In March 2018, Golden Entertainment announced plans for $140 million renovation of the Stratosphere that will be unveiled in three phases.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cdcgamingreports.com/golden-entertainment-unveils-140-million-plans-for-stratosphere-posted-fourth-quarter-loss/|title=Golden Entertainment unveils $140 million plans for Stratosphere, posted fourth-quarter loss|author=|date=|website=CDC Gaming Reports|accessdate=31 March 2018}}</ref> Golden Entertainment announced in February 2019 that the resort would be rebranded to The Strat Hotel, Casino and SkyPod.<ref name=\"Press\" /> The name change became official in January 2020.\n\n==History==\n{{Main|Vegas World}}\nIn 1974, [[Bob Stupak]] opened a small casino in [[Las Vegas]] known as Bob Stupak's World Famous Million-Dollar Historic Gambling Museum and Casino, located north of the [[Las Vegas Strip]] on land previously occupied by the Todkill/Bill Hayden [[Lincoln Motor Company|Lincoln]] [[Mercury (automobile)|Mercury]] Dealership.<ref name=\"Strip\">{{cite web|url=http://striplv.com/archives/19-articles/featured/517-the-men-who-made-las-vegas-bob-stupak-the-polish-maverick.html|title=The Men Who Made Las Vegas - Bob Stupak - The Polish Maverick|website=StripLV.com|year=2014|last=Craft|first=Byron|accessdate=2017-03-20}}</ref> The casino burned down two months later,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/8636642/the_daily_herald/|title=Museum-Casino Destroyed By Fire on Vegas 'Strip'|date=1974-05-22|work=[[Daily Herald (Utah)|Daily Herald]]|access-date=2017-03-20}}</ref> and Stupak subsequently opened his [[Vegas World]] hotel and casino on the same property in 1979.<ref name=May01/>\n\n===Conception===\nThe concept for the Stratosphere began as a plan by Stupak to construct a 1,012-foot (308.46 m) neon sign tower for Vegas World. In early October 1989, Stupak submitted plans to the city for the approval of the neon sign tower which would stand four times taller than the hotel. Later in the week, Stupak withdrew his plans to allow time for a revised version of the tower that would include an elevator leading up to an [[observation deck]]. Stupak, who wanted the tower to become a local landmark, said, \"What I'm trying to do for Las Vegas is what the [[Eiffel Tower]] did for [[Paris]], what the [[Empire State Building]] did for [[New York City|New York]], what the Seattle [[Space Needle]] did for [[Seattle]].\"<ref name=\"Landmark\">{{cite news|title=Stupak wants a landmark|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/9617823/reno_gazettejournal/|accessdate=2017-03-20|work=[[Reno Gazette-Journal]]|date=1989-10-07}}</ref><ref name=\"Sign\">{{cite news|title=Vegas council turns down sign ordinance|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/9617842/reno_gazettejournal/|accessdate=2017-03-20|work=Reno Gazette-Journal|date=1989-10-20}}</ref> Stupak's plans received widespread opposition,<ref name=Towers/> including from Las Vegas city staff, who drafted an [[Local ordinance|ordinance]] that would have limited signs to 35 feet in height.<ref name=Landmark/> The [[Las Vegas City Council]] rejected the ordinance, considering it to be a poorly drawn measure aimed specifically at stopping Stupak's project.<ref name=Sign/>\n\nIn February 1990, Stupak unveiled his revised plans for a $50 million, 1,012-foot observation tower with a top floor that would include a revolving restaurant and four penthouse suites.<ref>{{cite news|title=Revised plans unveiled|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/9617993/reno_gazettejournal/|accessdate=2017-03-20|work=Reno Gazette-Journal|date=1990-02-14}}</ref> In April 1990, the city council approved Stupak's tower, despite objections from the [[Federal Aviation Administration]] (FAA), which stated that it was 200 feet (61 m) too tall.<ref>{{cite news|title=Las Vegas approves tower|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/9618016/reno_gazettejournal/|accessdate=2017-03-20|work=Reno Gazette-Journal|date=1990-04-19}}</ref> [[Nellis Air Force Base]] also opposed the tower. Stupak later said that there were \"all sorts of people out there opposed\" to the tower, saying, \"If it wasn't for the courage of the council, it would have never been built.\"<ref name=May01/>\n\nIn October 1991, the city gave approval to the tower's base and shaft, while the pod atop the tower had yet to be approved. At the time, Stupak was trying to obtain financing for the now-$100 million project, and was also under investigation by gaming officials over allegations that he used [[Vegas World#Vacation packages|deceptive advertising]] to lure customers to Vegas World.<ref name=\"Daily\">{{cite web |last= |first= |title=Casino owner is given green light |url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/285778205/ |work=[[The Spectrum (Utah)|The Spectrum]] |date=1991-10-23 |accessdate=2019-02-08 |via=Newspapers.com|url-access=subscription }}</ref> The project was now planned to include the \"world's first indoor African lion's park,\"<ref name=Daily/> consisting of a jungle habitat to be located at the tower base.<ref name=Breaks/><ref>{{cite news|title=Circus Maximus|url=http://www.newsweek.com/circus-maximus-201700|accessdate=2017-03-20|work=[[Newsweek]]|date=1991-11-03}}</ref>\n\n[[Groundbreaking]] for the project, known as the Stratosphere Tower, took place on November 5, 1991.<ref name=Breaks/> The start of actual construction had yet to be announced for the tower, which was still opposed by the FAA.<ref name=\"Breaks\">{{cite web |last= |first= |title=Stupak breaks ground for tower project |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/9618463/reno_gazettejournal/ |work=Reno Gazette-Journal |date=1991-11-06 |accessdate=2019-02-08 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last= |first= |title=Vegas tower worries air official |url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/153161322/ |work=Reno Gazette-Journal |date=1991-10-26 |accessdate=2019-02-08 |via=Newspapers.com|url-access=subscription }}</ref> Originally, Stupak had envisioned an 1,800-foot tower, although the ultimate height was reduced to {{convert|1149|ft|abbr=on}} because of concerns from the FAA about possible interference with flights from the nearby [[McCarran International Airport]].<ref name=USA/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lasvegassun.com/news/2009/sep/25/bob-stupak-builder-stratosphere-and-vegas-world-di/ |title=Bob Stupak, builder of Stratosphere and Vegas World, dies at 67 |website=Las Vegas Sun |date= 2009-09-25 |accessdate=2016-03-12}}</ref> The tower was designed by architect Ned Baldwin, who also worked on the [[CN Tower]] in [[Toronto]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Carter|first=Geoff|title=Tourists For Breakfast: Designing Vegas|url=http://www.lasvegasweekly.com/2002/04_11/art_tfb.html|work=[[Las Vegas Weekly]]|date=April 2002|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020621082703/http://www.lasvegasweekly.com/2002/04_11/art_tfb.html|archivedate=2002-06-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Winsa |first=Patty |title=CN Tower built to last |url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/2014/02/23/cn_tower_built_to_last.html |accessdate=2019-07-18 |work=[[Toronto Star]] |date=2014-02-23}}</ref>\n\n===Construction===\n[[File:Western-towers.png|thumb|upright|\u2022 [[CN Tower]], Toronto<br />\u2022 [[Willis Tower]] (formerly Sears), Chicago<br />\u2022 Stratosphere, Las Vegas<br />\u2022 [[Space Needle]], Seattle]]\nConstruction of the $32 million tower began in February 1992, on property adjacent to Vegas World.<ref name=\"BattleCreek\">{{cite news|title=Fire engulfs observation tower|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/9618662/battle_creek_enquirer/|accessdate=2017-03-20|work=Associated Press|date=1993-08-30}}</ref> The tower was built directly north of the Las Vegas Strip<ref name=\"North\">{{cite web |title=Tower tries to stretch Strip boundary north of Sahara |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/1996/apr/26/tower-tries-to-stretch-strip-boundary-north-of-sah/ |work=Las Vegas Sun |date=1996-04-26 |accessdate=2019-02-08 }}</ref> and south of [[downtown Las Vegas]],<ref name=\"May01\">{{cite web|url=http://lasvegassun.com/news/2001/may/04/stupak-proud-but-not-notably-nostalgic-about-strat/|title=Stupak proud, but not notably nostalgic about Stratosphere|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=2001-05-04|accessdate=2019-02-08|first=Richard N.|last=Velotta}}</ref> in an area known as Meadows Village, a crime-ridden neighborhood nicknamed [[Naked City, Las Vegas|Naked City]].<ref name=\"Mean\">{{cite web |last=Zekan |first=Karen |title=Tower rises from mean streets |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/1996/apr/26/tower-rises-from-mean-streets/ |work=Las Vegas Sun |date=1996-04-26 |accessdate=2019-02-08 }}</ref> Shortly before its opening, a Stratosphere spokesman said, \"We hope Stratosphere will be the catalyst that spurs redevelopment\" in the area, while acknowledging, \"We plunked down a half-billion-dollar project in the middle of one of the worst neighborhoods.\"<ref name=Mean/>\n\nOn August 29, 1993, around midnight, hundreds of customers at Vegas World were evacuated when the half-finished tower caught on fire, during which no injuries occurred.<ref name=BattleCreek/><ref name=\"Rained\">{{cite web|author=Elizabeth Holland and Steve Sebelius |url=http://www.lasvegassun.com/news/1993/aug/30/tower-fire-rained-debris/ |title=Tower fire rained debris |website=Las Vegas Sun |date= 1993-08-30 |accessdate=2016-03-12}}</ref> The Stratosphere had been planned to open in August 1994, although the fire was expected to delay construction by eight weeks. Stupak said that the tower's first phase would still be ready in time with an accelerated construction schedule.<ref>{{cite news|title=Casino operator vows to finish building fire-damaged tower|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/9618683/reno_gazettejournal/|accessdate=2017-03-20|work=Reno Gazette-Journal|date=1993-09-03}}</ref> A large crane located atop the tower, used for construction, was also damaged in the fire.<ref name=Rained/><ref name=\"Winds\">{{cite news|title=Winds hamper tower work|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/9618706/reno_gazettejournal/|accessdate=2017-03-20|work=Reno Gazette-Journal|date=1993-09-13}}</ref> The following month, high winds prevented the scheduled dismantling of the crane, a process that was expected to take two days. At that time, the cause of the fire remained unknown.<ref name=Winds/> Following the fire,<ref name=Rave/> Stupak had trouble financing the completion of the tower.<ref name=May01/>\n\nTo continue construction,<ref name=Rave/> [[Grand Casinos]] announced plans in November 1993 to purchase 33 percent of the Stratosphere and Vegas World by acquiring shares in Stupak's Stratosphere Corporation.<ref>{{cite news|last=Marcotty|first=Josephine|title=Grand Casinos makes Vegas deal|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/9618745/star_tribune/|accessdate=2017-03-20|work=Star Tribune|date=1993-11-17}}</ref> Grand Casinos, owned by Stupak's poker friend [[Lyle Berman]], ultimately purchased a 43% stake in the resort.<ref name=Rave/> Vegas World closed on February 1, 1995, for remodeling in order to be integrated into the Stratosphere resort.<ref>{{cite news|title=Vacationers line up for World's last days|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/9619141/reno_gazettejournal/|accessdate=March 20, 2017|work=Reno Gazette-Journal|date=February 1, 1995}}</ref> Vegas World's two hotel towers,<ref name=RecNet/> consisting of 932 rooms,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://securities.stanford.edu/filings-documents/1002/GND96/001.html|title=Grand Casinos, Inc. Securities Litigation|publisher=Stanford University Law School|date=December 23, 1996|accessdate=May 23, 2015}}</ref> were renovated to become part of the Stratosphere.<ref name=\"RecNet\">{{cite web|url=http://www.recordnet.com/article/19950924/A_NEWS/309249984|title=Las Vegas reaches higher: 100-story roller coaster latest gamble for city|publisher=RecordNet.com|date=September 24, 1995|accessdate=May 23, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 1994, crews erected a crane \u2013 taller than the earlier one \u2013 that would allow them to continue work on the rising tower. The 75-ton crane stood 400 feet tall and was installed over the course of four days. Removal of the crane began in October 1995, with the use of a second crane. The dismantling of the crane was one of the most significant challenges for the people working on the tower. The unique design of the tower pod and its limit space required construction crews to carefully plan the installation of the second crane, which weighed 30 tons. The second crane would lower pieces of the original crane to the ground, and would then be used to lift a seven-ton [[derrick]] into place, allowing workers to carry down sections of the second crane. The derrick would then be disassembled by hand, and workers would use a construction elevator to bring down the pieces. The complex and risky process was expected to take nearly two months.<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |title=Workers dismantling crane |url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/477284277/ |work=Elko Daily Free Press |date=1995-10-11 |accessdate=2019-07-27 |via=Newspapers.com |url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nYears before the Stratosphere's opening, a three-block neighborhood of houses in Meadows Village was demolished to help make room for the resort's 4,500-space parking garage.<ref name=Mean/> In 1994,<ref name=LVS-Apr96/> officials from the Stratosphere project \u2013 located north of the [[Aztec Inn]] motel-casino<ref name=\"LVS2012\">{{cite web|url=http://lasvegassun.com/blogs/kats-report/2012/apr/06/new-and-improved-stratosphere-beacon-noble-risk-ta/|title=New-and-improved Stratosphere is a beacon of noble risk-taking|last=Katsilometes|first=John|date=2012-04-06|work=Las Vegas Sun|accessdate=2019-02-08}}</ref> \u2013 entered an agreement with the city's [[Las Vegas Redevelopment Agency]] to have the Aztec Inn's parking lot condemned through [[eminent domain]] and turned over to the Stratosphere.<ref name=\"LVS-Apr96\">{{cite web|url=http://lasvegassun.com/news/1996/apr/26/eminent-domain-redevelopment-issues-remain/|title=Eminent domain, redevelopment issues remain|last=Sebelius|first=Steve|date=1996-04-26|work=Las Vegas Sun|accessdate=2019-02-08}}</ref><ref name=\"LVRJ-Mar97\">{{cite web|url=http://www.lvrj.com/lvrj_home/1997/Mar-09-Sun-1997/news/4959608.html|title=They can fight city hall|last=Zapler|first=Mike|date=1997-03-09|work=[[Las Vegas Review-Journal]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19970719063545/http://www.lvrj.com/lvrj_home/1997/Mar-09-Sun-1997/news/4959608.html|archivedate=1997-07-19}}</ref> The agreement was opposed by the Aztec Inn,<ref name=LVS-Apr96/> and in 1995 was ruled by a judge to be unconstitutional.<ref name=LVRJ-Mar97/><ref name=LVS-Apr96/> By April 1996, the Aztec Inn settled with the Stratosphere and agreed to sell its parking lot.<ref name=LVS-Apr96/> Separately, the Stratosphere agreed to provide free rent and relocation expenses to approximately 140 residents in a nearby area of Meadows Village that was cleared for an eventual expansion of the resort.<ref>{{cite web |title=Residents Around Stratosphere Tower Evicted |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/1996/mar/19/residents-around-stratosphere-tower-evicted/ |work=Las Vegas Sun |date=1996-03-19 |accessdate=2019-02-08 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Sebelius |first=Steve |title=Evictions delayed for some Stratosphere neighbors |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/1996/mar/20/evictions-delayed-for-some-stratosphere-neighbors/ |work=Las Vegas Sun |date=1996-03-20 |accessdate=2019-02-08 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Residents near Stratosphere get aid |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/1996/mar/28/residents-near-stratosphere-get-aid/ |work=Las Vegas Sun |date=1996-03-28 |accessdate=2019-02-08 }}</ref><ref name=Mean/>\n\n[[File:T-240085515.jpg|thumb|right|Stratosphere pod during construction (September 1995)]]\nAfter a 1995 motorcycle accident that left Stupak in a [[coma]] for 12 days, he said that the controversy and \"all the complaining\" about the tower stopped: \"There were people who didn't like the tower, this and that, but after the accident, it was like nobody had anything negative to say about it.\"<ref name=May01/> As construction of the resort neared completion, one of the rides being planned for the resort was a giant ape that would carry riders up and down on one of the tower's columns.<ref>{{cite news|last=Dretzka|first=Gary|title=Vegas tower topped by roller coaster|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/9619227/south_florida_sun_sentinel/|accessdate=2017-03-20|work=Chicago Tribune|date=1996-01-28}}</ref> The ride was delayed in 1996,<ref>{{cite news |last=Schumacher |first=Geoff |title=King Kong delayed |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/1996/may/24/king-kong-delayed/ |accessdate=2019-02-09 |work=Las Vegas Sun |date=1996-05-24}}</ref> and ultimately cancelled.\n\nIn March 1996, the [[Nevada Gaming Control Board]] approved Stupak, the chairman of Stratosphere Corporation, for a [[gaming license]], along with other company individuals. Stupak owned 17 percent of Stratosphere Corporation, while Grand Casinos owned 43 percent. Stupak was one of nine directors in the company, and would not oversee daily operations of the company.<ref name=\"Problem\">{{cite web |last=Thompson |first=Gary |title=Gaming license no problem for Stupak |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/1996/mar/07/gaming-license-no-problem-for-stupak/ |work=Las Vegas Sun |date=1996-03-07 |accessdate=2019-02-08 }}</ref> The resort was expected to employ a total of 3,000 people, and began hiring for the remaining 2,400 employees in March 1996, a month before the opening. At the time, Stupak said he may resign his chairman position as soon as a month after the resort's opening, in order to pursue other projects.<ref>{{cite web |title=Commission gives final OK to Stratosphere plan |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/1996/mar/22/commission-gives-final-ok-to-stratosphere-plan/ |work=Las Vegas Sun |date=1996-03-22 |accessdate=2019-02-08 }}</ref>\n\nShortly before its opening, several [[Stunt performer|daredevil]]s had expressed an interest in performing stunts from the top of the tower, but they were declined for safety reasons.<ref name=\"Build\">{{cite web |title=Columnist: Build it and they will come |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/1996/apr/26/columnist-build-it-and-they-will-come/ |work=Las Vegas Sun |date=1996-04-26 |accessdate=2019-02-08 }}</ref> Smoke in the tower's pod restaurant forced an evacuation of workers on April 25, 1996, days before the opening. The smoke originated from the pod's fifth-floor kitchen, one floor above the restaurant, due to a faulty ventilator in the air-flow duct system. The pod contained four tanks with 32,000 gallons of water for firefighters in the event of a fire, but they were not needed.<ref>{{cite web |last=Scott |first=Cathy |title=Smoke, but no towering inferno |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/1996/apr/26/smoke-but-no-towering-inferno/ |work=Las Vegas Sun |date=1996-04-26 |accessdate=2019-02-08 }}</ref>\n\n===Opening===\nA film crew followed Stupak all day leading up to the opening.<ref name=May01/> More than 8,000 [[VIP]] guests visited the resort for a premiere party on the night of April 29, 1996, hours before its midnight opening. Stupak attended the event with singer [[Phyllis McGuire]]. Other attendees included Nevada governor [[Bob Miller (Nevada governor)|Bob Miller]] and Las Vegas mayor [[Jan Laverty Jones]].<ref name=Rave/><ref name=Silences/><ref>{{cite news |last=Shemeligian |first=Bob |title=Tower debut shaky if you didn't speak Stratosphere |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/1996/may/03/bob-sheneligian-tower-debut-shaky-if-you-didnt-spe/ |accessdate=2019-02-09 |work=Las Vegas Sun |date=1996-05-03}}</ref> Media from around the world also attended the event,<ref name=May01/> which was broadcast live by [[CNBC]] as well as television stations in Las Vegas and Los Angeles.<ref name=Rave/> A six-minute fireworks show, costing $50,000, began at 10:30&nbsp;p.m.<ref name=\"Rave\">{{cite web |last=Thompson |first=Gary |title=Tower draws rave reviews |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/1996/apr/30/tower-draws-rave-reviews/ |work=Las Vegas Sun |date=1996-04-30 |accessdate=2019-02-08 }}</ref><ref name=Silences/> Doors in the tower's pod had been left partially open to accommodate television camera cables, and smoke from the fireworks filled the pod and set off fire alarms, resulting in the shutdown of elevators and stranding hundreds of VIP guests.<ref>{{cite web |title=Smoke strands guests atop tower |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/1996/may/01/smoke-strands-guests-atop-tower/ |work=Las Vegas Sun |date=1996-05-01 |accessdate=2019-02-08 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Thompson |first=Gary |title=Bugs bedevil Stratosphere |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/1996/may/03/bugs-bedevil-stratosphere/ |work=Las Vegas Sun |date=1996-05-03 |accessdate=2019-02-09 }}</ref>\n\nThe $550 million complex featured {{convert|354000|sqft|abbr=on}},<ref name=Towers/> including {{convert|140000|sqft|abbr=on}} of entertainment and shopping space.<ref name=\"SF\">{{cite news |last=Robins |first=Cynthia |title=Las Vegas' Stratosphere is fit for the intrepid |url=https://www.sfgate.com/travel/article/Las-Vegas-Stratosphere-is-fit-for-the-intrepid-3142441.php |accessdate=2019-02-09 |work=SFGate |date=1996-05-26}}</ref> A {{convert|97000|sqft|abbr=on}} casino was part of the resort's first phase, which also included 1,500 hotel rooms. The hotel portion was expected to open on May 7, 1996.<ref name=\"Towers\">{{cite web |last=Thompson |first=Gary |title=New landmark towers over Las Vegas |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/1996/apr/26/new-landmark-towers-over-las-vegas/ |work=Las Vegas Sun |date=1996-04-26 |accessdate=2019-02-08 }}</ref> An additional 1,000 hotel rooms were expected to be finished in November 1996.<ref>{{cite web |title=Hospitality Network adds Stratosphere to its list |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/1996/feb/23/hospitality-network-adds-stratosphere-to-its-list/ |work=Las Vegas Sun |date=1996-02-23 |accessdate=2019-02-08 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Stratosphere by night.jpg|thumb|upright|right|The Stratosphere pod and needle at night.]]\nThe resort had 3,100 employees.<ref name=Rave/> The casino featured 2,600 slot machines, and was decorated with a [[world's fair]] theme and bright colors.<ref name=SF/> The casino was divided into three sections, each with their own international theme.<ref>{{cite news |last=Welling |first=Stacey |title=Topping 1,149 feet, $550-million Stratosphere shoots for the sky |url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/159062248/ |work=Los Angeles Times |date=1996-06-23 |accessdate=2019-07-27 |via=Newspapers.com |url-access=subscription}}</ref> The hotel included a bronze statue of Stupak, which he disliked and never approved, saying, \"They spent $100,000 more for that statue than I spent to open my first place in 1974.\"<ref name=May01/> Another statue, in the center of the casino, featured a couple riding a dolphin set upon a bronze globe.<ref name=SF/>\n\nThe tower cost $70 million to construct.<ref name=Mean/> The tower's pod contains 12 stories and has one and a half miles of criss-crossed [[fiber-optic cable]] with lights which alternate between eight different colors.<ref>{{cite web |last=Calkins |first=Alison |title=Diamond image helped designer see the light |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/1996/apr/26/diamond-image-helped-designer-see-the-light/ |work=Las Vegas Sun |date=1996-04-26 |accessdate=2019-02-08 }}</ref> A 149-foot needle<ref name=SF/> located on top of the pod consists of a five-square-foot steel-beam frame with an internal ladder. Atop the needle frame are two four-inch beams which are laid out horizontally to form an \"X\".<ref name=Build/> The observation deck rises 872 feet.<ref name=Figures/> The pod included two concrete-banded bunker floors, located beneath its three wedding chapels, for use in the event of an emergency.<ref name=SF/> Stupak's critics did not believe he would be able to complete the tower, in part because of his controversial promotional tactics at Vegas World.<ref name=Towers/><ref name=\"Silences\">{{cite web |last=German |first=Jeff |title=Stupak silences his critics with Stratosphere's opening |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/1996/apr/30/jeff-german-stupak-silences-his-critics-with-strat/ |work=Las Vegas Sun |date=1996-04-30 |accessdate=2019-02-08 }}</ref>\n\nAlthough the resort is located north of the Las Vegas Strip, it advertised itself as being on the Strip, with the slogan, \"We define the top of the Strip.\"<ref name=North/> The Stratosphere was projected to attract at least 5.5 million visitors in its first year.<ref name=\"Figures\">{{cite web |last=Thompson |first=Gary |title=It's not tallest, but tower figures to pile up revenue |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/1996/apr/26/its-not-tallest-but-tower-figures-to-pile-up-reven/ |work=Las Vegas Sun |date=1996-04-26 |accessdate=2019-02-08 }}</ref> Around the time of its opening, financial analysts were optimistic of the resort's future.<ref name=Towers/> Revenue for the first five weeks was lower than expected. Stratosphere Corporation attributed the low results to the resort being partly unfinished, and said it would borrow $48.5 million from Grand Casinos to finance enhancements to the property, including the completion of the 1,000 additional rooms, and the opening of unfinished retail shops.<ref>{{cite web |title=Stratosphere revenues less than predicted |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/1996/jun/07/stratosphere-revenues-less-than-predicted/ |work=Las Vegas Sun |date=1996-06-07 |accessdate=2019-02-08 }}</ref> The resort continued to suffer financially.<ref name=May01/><ref>{{cite news |last=Thompson |first=Gary |title=Troubles loom at Stratosphere |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/1996/jul/23/troubles-loom-at-stratosphere/ |accessdate=2019-07-27 |work=Las Vegas Sun |date=1996-07-23}}</ref>\n\n===Carl Icahn ownership===\n[[File:The Stratosphere Tower, Las Vegas, Nevada.jpg|thumb|Looking up from the base of the Stratosphere Tower, with the X-Scream ride hanging over the edge in 2009]]\nStupak, who had already made plans to move on to other projects,<ref name=Silences/> resigned as chairman less than three months after the opening, leaving Berman in charge. Stupak's statue was subsequently removed from the property.<ref name=May01/> The resort's second phase was halted in August 1996, due to financial problems;<ref name=\"Halts\">{{cite news |title=Stratosphere halts growth |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/1996/aug/30/stratosphere-halts-growth/ |work=Las Vegas Sun |date=1996-08-30 |accessdate=2019-07-27}}</ref> the additional hotel building consisted of an unfinished, 15-story structure of concrete and [[rebar]].<ref name=Retailers/> Berman intended to make the resort profitable, but ultimately declared bankruptcy in January 1997.<ref name=May01/> Stupak had previously called Berman \"the best casino operator in the world,\"<ref name=Problem/> but later said about Grand Casinos' operation of the resort, \"They just weren't up to it.\"<ref name=May01/>\n\n[[Carl Icahn]] planned to purchase the bankrupt resort. In mid-1997, Stupak made a plan to regain control of the Stratosphere by producing a half-hour video criticizing Grand Casinos' board members. Stupak also considered developing a bankruptcy plan of his own to compete against Icahn and Grand Casinos. Ultimately, Stupak's video never aired on local television as scheduled,<ref name=May01/> and Icahn gained control of the property in 1998.<ref name=Second/> In the years after Icahn took over, Stupak sometimes visited the Stratosphere's Top of the World restaurant but was otherwise disinterested in the resort. In 2001, Stupak stated that he felt prouder when he opened his earlier casinos on the site in 1974 and 1979. Stupak stated his biggest disappointment with the Stratosphere was not being able to have it built to his initially planned 1,800-foot height.<ref name=May01/>\n\nThe second hotel tower, with 24 stories, was [[Topping out|topped off]] on November 2, 2000.<ref name=\"Second\">{{cite news |title=Second tower at Stratosphere topped off |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/2000/nov/03/second-tower-at-stratosphere-topped-off/ |accessdate=2019-02-09 |work=Las Vegas Sun |date=2000-11-03}}</ref> The $65 million project included 1,002 rooms, a {{convert|67000|sqft|abbr=on}} pool and recreation area, and a coffee shop. Excluding the new tower, the hotel had 1,444 rooms. The new project was meant to improve business at the casino and its retail mall, the Tower Shops.<ref>{{cite news |title=Second Stratosphere tower topped off; to open next year |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/2000/nov/06/second-stratosphere-tower-topped-off-to-open-next-/ |accessdate=2019-02-09 |work=Las Vegas S |date=2000-11-06}}</ref> A major addition was completed in June 2001 for $1 billion that included finishing the second hotel tower.\n\n[[File:Stratosphere Las Vegas logo.svg|thumb|right|Stratosphere logo until 2019]]\nIn the early 2000s, the company attempted to get approval for a roller coaster that would run from several hundred feet up the tower and, in the last proposal, across [[Las Vegas Boulevard]]. Part of that last proposal included an entry monument on the ride over Las Vegas Boulevard welcoming people to the City of Las Vegas. The Las Vegas City Council did not approve the project due to objections from the neighbors over possible noise from the enclosed cars on the proposed ride.{{citation needed|date=February 2019}} Five people have committed suicide by jumping from the tower's observation area, between 2000 and 2007.<ref>{{cite news |last=Radke |first=Jace |title=Man jumps from Stratosphere Tower |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/2000/jan/07/man-jumps-from-stratosphere-tower/ |accessdate=2019-02-09 |work=Las Vegas Sun |date=2000-01-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Boy, 16, jumps from Stratosphere |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/2002/jul/15/boy-16-jumps-from-stratosphere/ |accessdate=2019-02-09 |work=Las Vegas Sun |date=2002-07-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Clarke |first=Norm |title=Tragedy follows 'Elvis' show work |url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/lvrj_home/2005/Mar-30-Wed-2005/news/26180561.html |work=Las Vegas Review-Journal |date=2005-03-30 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051130013343/http://www.reviewjournal.com/lvrj_home/2005/Mar-30-Wed-2005/news/26180561.html |archivedate=2005-11-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Stratosphere Jump: Investigation confirms woman killed herself |url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/lvrj_home/2005/Apr-13-Wed-2005/news/26280890.html |work=Las Vegas Review-Journal |date=2005-04-13 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051130010319/http://www.reviewjournal.com/lvrj_home/2005/Apr-13-Wed-2005/news/26280890.html |archivedate=2005-11-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Man jumps from Stratosphere tower |url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/lvrj_home/2006/Feb-08-Wed-2006/news/5774712.html |work=Las Vegas Review-Journal |date=2006-02-08 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070701202058/http://www.reviewjournal.com/lvrj_home/2006/Feb-08-Wed-2006/news/5774712.html |archivedate=2007-07-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Man killed in jump from Stratosphere |url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/news/in-brief-3294/ |work=Las Vegas Review-Journal |date=2007-05-07 |accessdate=2019-02-09}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2010, [[American Casino & Entertainment Properties]] announced a new thrill ride for the top of the tower: SkyJump, a controlled-descent, [[bungee jumping]]\u2013like ride that would allow riders to plummet {{convert|855|ft|m}} attached to a high-speed descent wire. It opened on April 20, 2010.<ref name=\"aaavegas1\">{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.aaavegas.com/attractions/the-stratosphere-las-vegas-hotel-casino-to-add-worlds-highest-skyjump%E2%80%9D-to-their-collection-of-thrills/2010/01/11 |title=The Stratosphere Las Vegas Hotel & Casino To Add World's Highest \"Skyjump\" To Their Collection Of Thrills &#124; AccessVegas.com Las Vegas News |website=Aaavegas.com |date=2013-01-24 |accessdate=2016-03-12}}</ref>\n\n[[File:The Stratosphere Las Vegas 2 Bay FM Antenna.jpg|thumb|right|upright|KOAS-FM1 and KVGS-FM1 transmitting antenna atop the Stratosphere, 2010.]]\nRadio stations [[KOAS|KOAS 105.7 (FM)]] and [[KVGS|KVGS 107.9 (FM)]] have on-channel FM boosters broadcasting from an antenna at the top of the tower's structure. Licensed as KOAS-FM1 and KVGS-FM1, they are the only radio stations with transmitters at the tower. However, the signals being transmitted from this structure are relatively low-power and only cover the immediate Las Vegas area on a \"fill in\" or \"booster\" basis. Both of these stations have their main transmitter sites located elsewhere, and those transmitter sites are what give these stations more widespread regional coverage.\n\nBeginning in 2010, the Stratosphere renovated several areas of the property. As part of a $20 million renovation plan, improvements were made to many hotel rooms, the casino, and the main entrance area. Improvements and upgrades have also been made in the Top of the World Restaurant and Level 107 lounge.<ref name=20-million/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/business/skyjump-renovations-seen-boost-stratosphere-parent |title=SkyJump, renovations seen as boost for Stratosphere parent |website=Las Vegas Review-Journal |date=2010-05-12 |accessdate=2016-03-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.vegaschatter.com/story/2011/1/14/92236/5315/vegas-travel/The+Stratosphere+Has+Pretty+New+Rooms+with+a+View+of+the+Fontaine-Bust |title=Things To Do In Las Vegas - Attractions & Travel Guide - Cond\u00e9 Nast Traveler |website=Vegaschatter.com |date= |accessdate=2016-03-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Sylvester |first=Ron |url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/765567867/Stratosphere-renovations-give-Vegas-icon-new-mojo.html?pg=all |title=Stratosphere renovations give Vegas icon new mojo |publisher=Deseret News |date=2012-04-11 |accessdate=2016-03-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Warren Mason |url=http://mylifemagazine.com/the-new-stratosphere |title=The 'New' Stratosphere |website=Mylifemagazine.com |date= |accessdate=2016-03-12}}</ref>\n\n===Golden Entertainment===\nIn June 2017, [[Golden Entertainment]] agreed to purchase American Casino & Entertainment Properties.<ref>{{cite news|title=Iconic Stratosphere casino in Las Vegas changes hands|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/iconic-stratosphere-casino-in-las-vegas-changes-hands/2017/06/12/e53e3f58-4fa2-11e7-b74e-0d2785d3083d_story.html|accessdate=2017-06-12|work=The Washington Post|agency=Associated Press|date=2017-06-22}}</ref> Golden Entertainment's $850 million purchase of the company, including the Stratosphere, was completed in October 2017.<ref name=\"reviewjournal.com\"/>\n\nIn March 2018, Golden Entertainment announced plans for a $140 million renovation of the Stratosphere that will be completed over three phases.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/business/casinos-gaming/golden-entertainment-to-invest-140m-in-stratosphere/|title=Golden Entertainment to invest $140M in Stratosphere|author=|date=15 March 2018|website=Las Vegas Review-Journal|accessdate=31 March 2018}}</ref> On February 1, 2019, plans were announced to rename the resort as The STRAT Hotel, Casino and SkyPod.<ref name=\"Press\">{{cite web |title=Golden Entertainment, Inc. Announces Stratosphere Rebrand to 'The STRAT' |url=https://www.stratospherehotel.com/Flyers/Press/2019-Press-Releases/Golden-Entertainment-Inc.-Announces-Stratosphere-Rebrand-to-The-STRAT |publisher=Golden Entertainment |accessdate=2019-02-09 |date=2019-02-04|quote=On Sunday, Feb. 3, the Stratosphere, Casino, Hotel & Tower began its transition to The STRAT Hotel, Casino and SkyPod [\u2026].}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Prince |first=Todd |title=Stratosphere in Las Vegas to rebrand to The STRAT |url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/business/casinos-gaming/stratosphere-in-las-vegas-to-rebrand-to-the-strat-1587571/ |accessdate=February 2, 2019 |work=Las Vegas Review-Journal |date=February 1, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Philly\">{{cite news |title=Stratosphere casino-hotel in Las Vegas to be renamed |url=http://www.philly.com/news/nation-world/stratosphere-vegas-the-strat-casino-skypod-20190202.html |accessdate=February 2, 2019 |work=[[Philly.com]] |agency=Associated Press |date=February 1, 2019}}</ref> For years, \"The Strat\" had been used by local residents as a nickname.<ref>{{cite news |last=Radke |first=Brock |title=The Stratosphere is rebranding to the STRAT |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/2019/feb/02/stratosphere-rebranding-the-strat/ |accessdate=2019-02-09 |work=Las Vegas Sun |date=2019-02-02}}</ref> The transition to The Strat began with two commercials aired locally two days later during [[Super Bowl LIII]].<ref name=Philly/><ref name=\"Klas\">{{cite news |last=Hopkins |first=Justin |title=Goodbye Stratosphere, hello Strat |url=https://www.lasvegasnow.com/news/local-news/goodbye-stratosphere-hello-strat/1761737195 |accessdate=2019-02-09 |work=KLAS-TV |date=2019-02-07}}</ref> The name change would become official at a later date.<ref name=Klas/>\n\nA three-piece statue, created by local artists, was installed at the resort's front entrance in April 2019. The statue consists of three stainless steel figures staring at the tower. They range in height from 9 to 15 feet, with the tallest one pointing at the tower. [[Blake Sartini]], the chairman and CEO of Golden Entertainment, said the statue was a symbol of the resort's new branding. He also said, \"We wanted to create a piece that people would use as a 'wow' moment, an [[Instagram]] moment.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Karel |first=Janna |title='Look!' Strat installs local art piece on Las Vegas Boulevard |url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/entertainment/arts-culture/look-strat-installs-local-art-piece-on-las-vegas-boulevard-1644501/ |accessdate=2019-12-06 |work=Las Vegas Review-Journal |date=2019-04-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Seeman |first=Matthew |title=New sculpture unveiled outside entrance to The STRAT |url=https://news3lv.com/news/local/new-sculpture-unveiled-outside-entrance-to-the-strat |accessdate=2019-12-06 |work=KSNV |date=2019-04-19}}</ref> Two areas for live entertainment \u2013 one on the casino floor and one in the former space of a lounge \u2013 were being added in June 2019,<ref name=Kat2019/> as well as a new slot machine lounge.<ref name=\"Schulz\">{{cite news |last=Schulz |first=Bailey |title=STRAT updates bring competition for north Las Vegas Strip, analysts say |url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/business/strat-updates-bring-competition-for-north-las-vegas-strip-analysts-say-1760495/ |accessdate=2019-07-27 |work=Las Vegas Review-Journal |date=2019-07-19}}</ref> A glass walkway looking down 109 floors was expected to be complete by late 2020, along with the modernization and refurbishment of approximately 1,000 rooms.<ref name=Kat2019/> \"STRAT\" signage was installed in August 2019,<ref>{{cite news |title=Hooters Hotel sold, Strat new marquee on display |url=https://www.8newsnow.com/news/local-news/hooters-hotel-sold-strat-new-marquee-on-display/ |accessdate=2019-08-27 |work=KLAS |date=2019-08-26 |at=1:15}}</ref> and renovations on the south end of the casino floor were completed that year.<ref>{{cite news |last=Horwath |first=Bryan |title=New Strat boss has high hopes for property's new vibe, north Strip |url=https://vegasinc.lasvegassun.com/business/gaming/2019/nov/20/former-caesars-exec-hopes-stickiness-strat-leads/ |accessdate=2019-11-30 |work=VegasInc |date=2019-11-20}}</ref> Other renovations have included the resort's exterior and landscaping.<ref name=Velotta>{{cite news |last=Velotta |first=Richard N. |title=Golden Entertainment hopes renovations of The Strat boost earnings |url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/business/casinos-gaming/golden-entertainment-hopes-renovations-of-the-strat-boost-earnings-1887936/ |accessdate=2019-11-30 |work=Las Vegas Review-Journal |date=2019-11-07}}</ref> The Strat also installed [[Unmanned aerial vehicle|drone]] detection technology, alerting the property whenever illegal drones are flown near the tower.<ref>{{cite news |last=Pretty |first=Ted |title=The Strat uses new drone detection technology on Las Vegas Strip |url=https://www.fox5vegas.com/news/local/the-strat-uses-new-drone-detection-technology-on-las-vegas/article_8817f640-00d3-11ea-98db-171fe42e7cdb.html |accessdate=2019-11-30 |work=KVVU |date=2019-11-13}}</ref>\n\nThe resort was officially renamed The Strat Hotel, Casino and SkyPod during a celebration held on January 22, 2020. Among the attendees to the event were Nevada governor [[Steve Sisolak]], congresswoman [[Dina Titus]], [[Sammy Hagar]], [[Guy Fieri]], and [[Rick Springfield]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Sammy Hagar, Rick Springfield celebrate reinvention of The STRAT |url=https://www.ktnv.com/positivelylv/rock-icon-sammy-hagar-and-rick-springfield-celebrate-reinvention-of-the-strat |accessdate=2020-01-24 |work=KTNV |date=2020-01-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Miller |first=Cody |title=Sammy Hagar, Rick Springfield join Governor Sisolak for reopening of The STRAT |url=https://news3lv.com/news/local/sammy-hagar-rick-springfield-join-governor-sisolak-for-reopening-of-the-strat |accessdate=2020-01-24 |work=KSNV |date=2020-01-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Mancini |first=Al |title=Sammy Hagar to be guest bartender at The Strat on Jan. 22 |url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/entertainment/food/sammy-hagar-to-be-guest-bartender-at-the-strat-on-jan-22-1932810/ |accessdate=2020-01-24 |work=Las Vegas Review-Journal |date=2020-01-10}}</ref> Renovations were largely finished at the time, with the exception of a self-check-in area and remodeling that was scheduled to begin on the casino's north side during the second quarter of 2020. Half of the resort's 2,472 hotel rooms had been remodeled, and future renovations would also take place on the remaining rooms. The {{convert|80000|sqft|abbr=on}} casino, considered dark before, was remodeled with a new color scheme and an open layout. A new [[William Hill (bookmaker)|William Hill]] sports book was also added.<ref name=Schulz2>{{cite news |last=Schulz |first=Bailey |title=Strat's $100M renovation project nears completion |url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/business/casinos-gaming/strats-100m-renovation-project-nears-completion-1940283/ |accessdate=2020-01-14 |work=Las Vegas Review-Journal |date=2020-01-21}}</ref> The renovations, including four new restaurants, were designed to retain customers who usually only visited the pod area.<ref name=Klas/><ref name=Schulz2/> The renovation was also intended to help the property compete against nearby rivals, including upcoming resorts \u2013 [[The Drew Las Vegas|The Drew]] and [[Resorts World Las Vegas|Resorts World]] \u2013 as well as the renovated [[Sahara Las Vegas|Sahara]].<ref name=Schulz/>\n\n==Attractions and entertainment==\n[[File:Stratosphere Las Vegas -8Sept2008.jpg|upright|thumb|View from the top of the Stratosphere Tower in 2008]]\nThe top of the tower has two [[observation deck]]s, a [[revolving restaurant]] known as \"Top of the World\", and four thrill rides.\n\nAn indoor observation deck is located on the 108th floor, and includes food and beverage outlets, while stairs lead up to the outdoor deck on the 109th floor. Both decks provide wraparound views of the [[Las Vegas Valley]]. The indoor deck was remodeled and unveiled in July 2019.<ref name=\"KTNV\">{{cite news |last=Dinant |first=Jason |title=Remodeled STRAT observation deck debuts |url=https://www.ktnv.com/positivelylv/dining-and-entertainment/remodeled-strat-observation-deck-debuts |accessdate=2019-07-26 |work=KTNV |date=2019-07-22}}</ref>\n\n===Rides===\nRides at the Stratosphere include:\n*[[Big Shot (ride)|Big Shot]] at {{convert|1081|ft|abbr=on}} was the highest [[Amusement ride|thrill ride]] in the world until the Sky Drop opened on the [[Canton Tower]] at {{convert|1591|ft|abbr=on}}.\n*[[Insanity (ride)|Insanity]], opened in 2005, at {{convert|900|ft|abbr=on}} is the third highest thrill ride in the world; it dangles riders over the edge of the tower and then spins in a circular pattern at approximately forty miles per hour.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vegas.com/attractions/on-the-strip/stratosphere-insanity/ |website=www.vegas.com |title=Stratosphere insanity|accessdate=7 January 2019}}</ref> In a 2005 incident, riders were left dangling several hundred feet above the Las Vegas Strip for nearly an hour and a half when Insanity shut down; it was programmed to cease operation if a fault or problem is detected by the ride's control system.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/lvrj_home/2005/Apr-21-Thu-2005/news/26341046.html |last=Rogers |first=Keith |title=Teen, cousin suffer night of Insanity |website=Las Vegas Review-Journal |date=2005-04-21 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050423181225/http://www.reviewjournal.com/lvrj_home/2005/Apr-21-Thu-2005/news/26341046.html |archivedate=2005-04-23}}</ref>\n*[[SkyJump Las Vegas]], a controlled-descent, Bungee-jumping-like ride that allows riders to plummet {{convert|855|ft|abbr=on}} attached to a high-speed descent wire.<ref name=\"aaavegas1\"/> SkyJump opened on April 20, 2010.<ref>{{cite news |last=Winder |first=Carl |title=He's Sky Master at the Vegas Stratosphere: 'I throw people off' |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2013/may/18/nation/la-na-nn-sky-master-las-vegas-stratosphere-20130517 |accessdate=2019-02-09 |work=Los Angeles Times |date=2013-05-18}}</ref>\n*[[X-Scream]] at {{convert|866|ft|abbr=on}} is the fourth highest thrill ride in the world. It consists of a single car that rolls back and forth on a straight piece of track that slightly overhangs the tower and pivots vertically in a [[see-saw]] motion.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stratospherehotel.com/ThrillRides/X-Scream|title=X-Scream|website=Stratosphere Hotel Tower and Casino|language=en|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref>\n\nA previous ride, the [[High Roller (Stratosphere)|High Roller]], closed on December 30, 2005, and was dismantled.<ref name=LVM/> At {{convert|909|ft|abbr=on}}<ref>{{cite web|author=Stratosphere Hotel Las Vegas |url=http://www.lasvegastourism.com/stratosp.htm |title=Stratosphere Las Vegas, Official Site |website=Lasvegastourism.com |date= |accessdate=2016-03-12}}</ref> it was the second highest ride in the world and the highest [[roller coaster]].<ref name=\"LVM\">{{cite web|author= |url=http://lasvegasmagazine.com/entertainment/2014/apr/25/9-views-las-vegas/#/0 |title=9 Views of Las Vegas to Soak In |publisher=Las Vegas Magazine |date=2014-04-25 |accessdate=2016-03-12}}</ref>\n\n===Tower Shops===\nThe Tower Shops is a mall on the second level. The elevators that lead up to the observation decks are only accessible in the mall.<ref name=Rising/> [[Edward J. DeBartolo Sr.|DeBartolo Realty Corporation]], which owned a 50-percent interest in the Tower Shops, was acquired by [[Simon Property Group]] in March 1996, forming Simon DeBartolo Group.<ref name=Retailers/> The Tower Shops were a joint venture between Simon DeBartolo Group and Gordon Group, under the name Strato-Retail.<ref name=\"Headache\">{{cite news |last=Strow |first=David |title=Icahn hopes to ease resort's mall headache by buying it |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/2000/sep/25/icahn-hopes-to-ease-resorts-mall-headache-by-buyin/ |work=Las Vegas Sun |date=2000-09-25 |accessdate=2019-07-27}}</ref> The Stratosphere leased the retail space to Strato-Retail, which then [[sublease]]d it to retail tenants.<ref name=Sued/>\n\nWhen the Stratosphere opened in April 1996, its retail area was still largely under construction and consisted only of vendor carts spread across three areas with their own theme: Chinese, French, and Manhattan.<ref name=SF/> The mall was built by Missouri construction company McCarthy, which was finishing the first phase in May 1996.<ref name=\"Rising\">{{cite news |title=McCarthy's Big Vegas Project Rising To Stratosphere |url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/142523619/ |accessdate=2019-07-26 |work=St. Louis Post-Dispatch |date=1996-05-27 |via=Newspapers.com |url-access=subscription}}</ref> The next phase of the Tower Shops was halted in August 1996,<ref name=Halts/><ref>{{cite web |last= |first= |title=The Sky was the Limit//The Stratosphere's Tower Shops Reached for the Stars, Literally and Financially, but Have Failed to Fulfill Expectations |url=https://nl.newsbank.com |website=St. Paul Pioneer Press |accessdate=2019-07-27 |date=1996-09-27 |url-access=subscription |via=NewsLibrary}}</ref> leaving the mall with {{convert|69000|sqft|abbr=on}} of retail space.<ref name=NewShops/><ref name=Headache/> The second phase, scheduled for completion in December 1996, would have increased the mall to {{convert|160000|sqft|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |title=Stratosphere opens grand tower, resort |url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/159256112/ |work=Los Angeles Times |date=1996-04-07 |accessdate=2019-07-27 |via=Newspapers.com |url-access=subscription}}</ref> The second phase would have included a [[Rainforest Cafe]] as its main [[anchor tenant]].<ref name=Retailers/><ref name=Headache/> A Kids Quest child-care center was also planned as part of the second phase.<ref>{{cite web |last=Calkins |first=Alison |title=Tower has a place just for kids |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/1996/apr/26/tower-has-a-place-just-for-kids/ |work=Las Vegas Sun |date=1996-04-26 |accessdate=2019-02-08 }}</ref><ref name=Retailers/> As of February 1997, the mall had 32 of 45 stores opened, with the remainder expected to be open by the end of the second quarter. The mall had approximately 300 employees.<ref name=\"NewShops\">{{cite web |last=Caruso |first=Monica |title=Stratosphere continues to open new shops |url=http://www.lvrj.com/lvrj_home/1997/Feb-14-Fri-1997/business/4863616.html |work=Las Vegas Review-Journal |date=February 14, 1997 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19970719140852/http://www.lvrj.com/lvrj_home/1997/Feb-14-Fri-1997/business/4863616.html |archivedate=July 19, 1997}}</ref> As of October 1997, there were 36 stores, including a clothing store owned by Las Vegas mayor [[Jan Laverty Jones|Jan Jones]],<ref>{{cite web |last=Zapler |first=Mike |title=Jones runs business at casino she regulates |url=http://www.lvrj.com/lvrj_home/1997/Oct-09-Thu-1997/news/6205654.html |work=Las Vegas Review-Journal |date=October 9, 1997 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20000918160736/http://www.lvrj.com/lvrj_home/1997/Oct-09-Thu-1997/news/6205654.html |archivedate=September 18, 2000}}</ref> who also owned shares in Grand Casinos.<ref name=Jones/> Approximately 85 percent of the retail space was occupied, and 98 percent was leased.<ref name=\"Jones\">{{cite web |last=Zapler |first=Mike |title=Jones offers defense of casino lease |url=http://www.lvrj.com/lvrj_home/1997/Oct-16-Thu-1997/news/6248272.html |work=Las Vegas Review-Journal |date=October 16, 1997 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20000918173617/http://www.lvrj.com/lvrj_home/1997/Oct-16-Thu-1997/news/6248272.html |archivedate=September 18, 2000}}</ref>\n\nBy 1998, retailers in the Tower Shops were experiencing financial difficulties and lack of customer traffic, which the retailers blamed on the resort's unfinished facilities.<ref name=\"Retailers\">{{cite news |last=Shemeligian |first=Bob |title=Stratosphere retailers say they're hurting |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/1998/jan/26/stratosphere-retailers-say-theyre-hurting/ |accessdate=2019-07-26 |work=Las Vegas Sun |date=1998-01-26}}</ref> Strato-Retail filed suits against several of the mall's retailers, alleging non-payment of rent. Two retailers that were locked in for expensive, long-term leases filed suits against Strato-Retail.<ref name=Retailers/><ref name=\"Sued\">{{cite news |title=Retailer sued over rent |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/1999/aug/12/retailer-sued-over-rent/ |work=Las Vegas Sun |date=1999-08-12 |accessdate=2019-07-27}}</ref> As of March 1999, the Stratosphere planned to add a new escalator which the resort said would lead up to the casino's showroom. However, Strato-Retail sued Stratosphere Corporation, alleging that the escalator would hinder business to the Tower Shops by allowing visitors to bypass the mall on their way to the top of the observation tower. The resort denied that the escalator could be used to access the tower.<ref>{{cite news |title=Stratosphere sued by retailers over escalator |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/1999/mar/25/stratosphere-sued-by-retailers-over-escalator/ |work=Las Vegas Sun |date=1999-03-25 |accessdate=2019-07-27}}</ref> Strato-Retail won a permanent injunction against the escalator's construction.<ref name=Take-Over/>\n\nIn 2000, Stratosphere Corporation purchased the mall from Strato-Retail for $12.5 million.<ref>{{cite news |title=Icahn buying Stratosphere mall, taking resort private |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/2000/sep/20/icahn-buying-stratosphere-mall-taking-resort-priva/ |work=Las Vegas Sun |date=2000-09-20 |accessdate=2019-07-27}}</ref><ref name=Headache/><ref name=\"Take-Over\">{{cite news |title=Company pays $12.5 million to take over mall |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/2000/nov/13/company-pays-125-million-to-take-over-mall/ |work=Las Vegas Sun |date=2000-11-13 |accessdate=2019-07-27}}</ref> In 2004, the Tower Shops had {{convert|110000|sqft|abbr=on}} of retail space, which was approximately 90 leased. That year, the mall announced plans for an additional {{convert|80000|sqft|abbr=on}} of retail space.<ref name=Shubinski/><ref>{{cite news |last=Illia |first=Tony |title=Trade show brings rash of new project announcements |url=http://lvbusinesspress.com:80/articles/2004/05/28/columnists/col02realestate.txt |work=Las Vegas Business Press |date=2004-05-28 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040606065448/http://lvbusinesspress.com:80/articles/2004/05/28/columnists/col02realestate.txt |archivedate=2004-06-04}}</ref> The expansion would occupy undeveloped space that was meant for the Tower Shops' originally planned second phase.<ref name=\"Shubinski\">{{cite news |last=Shubinski |first=Jennifer |title=Stratosphere plans Tower Shops growth |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/2004/may/21/stratosphere-plans-tower-shops-growth/ |work=Las Vegas Sun |date=2004-05-21 |accessdate=2019-07-27}}</ref> At the time, the mall had approximately 50 stores and 15 retail carts.<ref>{{cite web |last=Smith |first=Hubble |title=Strip getting a slice of the island |url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/lvrj_home/2004/May-25-Tue-2004/business/23954996.html |work=Las Vegas Review-Journal |date=May 25, 2004 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050128011208/http://www.reviewjournal.com/lvrj_home/2004/May-25-Tue-2004/business/23954996.html |archivedate=January 28, 2005}}</ref>\n\n===Performers===\nThe casino has featured a number of performers, including bands and dancers. Frankie Moreno Live at Stratosphere had its final performance on December 20, 2014. Moreno and his 10-piece band began performing in the Stratosphere Theater on November 9, 2011 and achieved nearly 600 shows during his three-year tenure at the Stratosphere.\n\n[[Playboy Playmate]] [[List of Playboy Playmates of 2010#October|Claire Sinclair]] signed for a new show in 2013, and re-signed for 2015. David Perrico with the band Pop Evolution, signed in 2013 for a monthly show.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lasvegassun.com/blogs/kats-report/2014/dec/19/moreno-hitting-carnegie-hall-2015-wynn-gives-dance/ |title=Frankie Moreno hitting Carnegie Hall in 2015; Wynn gives 'Showstoppers' dancers room to stretch legs |website=Las Vegas Sun |date=2014-12-19 |accessdate=2016-03-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Leach |first=Robin |url=http://lasvegassun.com/vegasdeluxe/2014/dec/19/showstoppers-frankie-moreno-brian-setzer-penny-pib/ |title=Celebrity preview: 'Showstoppers,' Moreno, Setzer, Pibbets, Meryl Davis + Charlie White |website=Las Vegas Sun |date=2014-12-19 |accessdate=2016-03-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.vegaschatter.com/tag/Frankie%20Moreno |title=Things To Do In Las Vegas - Attractions & Travel Guide - Cond\u00e9 Nast Traveler |website=Vegaschatter.com |date= |accessdate=2016-03-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Hall |first=Debbie |url=http://www.axs.com/las-vegas-headliner-frankie-moreno-schedules-final-performance-at-stra-24008 |title=Las Vegas headliner Frankie Moreno schedules final performance at Stratosphere |website=AXS.com |date=2014-10-18 |accessdate=2016-03-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Mike Weatherford |url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/entertainment/entertainment-columns/mike-weatherford/pin-up-displaying-more-vintage-cool/ |title='Pin Up' displaying more vintage cool |website=Las Vegas Review-Journal |date=2014-09-01 |accessdate=2019-02-08}}</ref>\n\nThe Strat added an acrobatic show, Celestia, in June 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last=Katsilometes |first=John |title='Celestia' gathers familiar acts under one tent on Las Vegas Strip |url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/entertainment/entertainment-columns/kats/celestia-gathers-familiar-acts-under-one-tent-on-las-vegas-strip-1682244/ |accessdate=2020-01-24 |work=Las Vegas Review-Journal |date=2019-06-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Radke |first=Brock |title=The STRAT's new 'Celestia' could be a summer family hit |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/2019/jun/10/celestia-strat-circus-show-review/ |accessdate=2020-01-24 |work=Las Vegas Sun |date=2019-06-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Mills |first=Heather |title='Celestia' brings death-defying entertainment to Las Vegas Strip |url=https://news3lv.com/news/local/celestia-brings-death-defying-entertainment-to-las-vegas-strip |accessdate=2020-01-24 |work=KSNV |date=2019-12-06}}</ref> The show is performed inside a {{convert|30000|sqft|abbr=on}} tent located outside the Strat.<ref name=Schulz2/>\n\n==Dining==\n*Top of the World\n*McCall's Heartland Grill\n*Fellini's Ristorante\n*Roxy's Diner\n*The Buffet\n*Level 8 Pool Cafe\n*Tower Pizzeria\n*Starbucks\n*Level 107 Lounge\n\n==Gaming==\nSome of the casino games include [[slot machine]]s and [[video poker]]. The Stratosphere has inherited some unusual variations on casino games from its predecessor. The {{convert|80000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} casino includes 50 table games, 1,500 slot and video poker machines, a [[poker]] room, and a race and [[sports book]].\n\n==In popular culture==\n*In 1999, scenes for the game show ''[[Real World/Road Rules Challenge 2000]]'' were filmed involving contestants bungee jumping from the Stratosphere's tower.<ref name=\"Cling\">{{cite news |last=Cling |first=Carol |title=Fall TV season keeps Vegas hopping with business |url=http://www.lvrj.com/lvrj_home/1999/Sep-27-Mon-1999/lifestyles/12020643.html |work=Las Vegas Review-Journal |date=1999-09-27 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010430142649/http://www.lvrj.com/lvrj_home/1999/Sep-27-Mon-1999/lifestyles/12020643.html |archivedate=2001-04-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Clarke |first=Norm |title=MTV adventurers' wake-up call: bungee jump from Stratosphere |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/sites/lvrb/ |accessdate=2019-02-09 |work=Las Vegas Review-Journal |date=1999-09-29|url-access=subscription }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Leong |first=Grace |title=Bungee jumping resumes at Stratosphere |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/1999/sep/30/bungee-jumping-resumes-at-stratosphere/ |accessdate=2019-02-09 |work=Las Vegas Sun |date=1999-09-30}}</ref>\n*The Stratosphere was also used in 1999 for filming of the television series ''[[The Strip (U.S. TV series)|The Strip]]''.<ref name=Cling/>\n*The casino and tower are featured in the 2005 movie ''[[Domino (2005 film)|Domino]]'', in which the owner gets robbed of $10 million and the top of the tower gets damaged in an explosion.<ref>{{cite web |title=STRATOSPHERE CASINO LANDS EXPLOSIVE MOVIE PROMOTION |url=https://adage.com/article/madisonvine-case-study/stratosphere-casino-lands-explosive-movie-promotion/47196/ |website=adage.com |accessdate=7 January 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n*The tower is the inspiration for the Vertigo Spire location/map featured in the 2006 video game ''[[Tom Clancy's Rainbow Six: Vegas]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Miller |first1=Jonathan |title=Rainbow Six Vegas: A Night on the Town |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2006/11/02/rainbow-six-vegas-a-night-on-the-town |website=IGN |accessdate=7 January 2019 |date=1 November 2006}}</ref>\n*In the History Channel's ''[[Life After People]]'', the tower is destroyed by an earthquake in the 2009 episode \"Sin City Meltdown\".\n*The tower is the inspiration of the fictional Lucky 38 casino in the 2010 role-playing game ''[[Fallout: New Vegas]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Location 23: The Strip - Lucky 38 |url=http://www.falloutnewvegastour.com/2011/04/location-23-strip-lucky-38.html |accessdate=7 January 2019}}</ref>\n*In 2013, the tower was featured in episode 24 of the [[HaMerotz LaMillion 3|third season]] of the [[HaMerotz LaMillion|Israeli edition of ''The Amazing Race'']] as part of a Roadblock task where contestants had to jump off of the tower on the SkyJump.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/hamerotz/photos/a.129167740489202/513124708760168/?type=3&theater|script-title=he:\u05de\u05d9 \u05de\u05d4\u05d6\u05d5\u05d2\u05d5\u05ea \u05d9\u05e2\u05e9\u05d4 \u05d9\u05d5\u05ea\u05e8, \u05d9\u05e6\u05dc\u05d9\u05d7 \u05d9\u05d5\u05ea\u05e8 \u05d5\u05d1\u05e2\u05d9\u05e7\u05e8 \u05d9\u05d4\u05d9\u05d4 \u05d0\u05de\u05d9\u05e5 \u05d9\u05d5\u05ea\u05e8?? \u05e6\u05e4\u05d5 \u05d1\u05d4\u05e6\u05e6\u05d4 \u05dc\u05e4\u05e8\u05e7 \u05d4\u05d1\u05d0 \u05d5\u05d2\u05dc\u05d5 \u05de\u05d9 \u05de\u05d4\u05e6\u05d5\u05d5\u05ea\u05d9\u05dd \u05d4\u05ea\u05d2\u05d1\u05e8 \u05e2\u05dc \u05e4\u05d7\u05d3 \u05d4\u05d2\u05d1\u05d4\u05d9\u05dd>>|language=Hebrew|trans-title=Which of the couples will do more, be more successful and most of all be braver ?? Watch the glimpse of the next chapter and find out which team has overcome the fear of heights >>|work=[[Facebook]]|date=August 2, 2013|accessdate=December 31, 2019}}</ref>\n*In the 2014 [[Syfy]] television series ''[[Dominion (TV series)|Dominion]]'', the archangel Michael lived in the observation tower of the Stratosphere.<ref>{{cite web |title=Dominion TV show setting |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/tv/syfys-dominion-survivng-the-post-apocalypse-with-some-low-rent-angels/2014/06/18/e7670e40-f64f-11e3-a3a5-42be35962a52_story.html?noredirect=on |accessdate=7 January 2019}}</ref>\n*A replica of the tower can be found in the 2014 racing game ''[[The Crew (video game)|The Crew]]'', in the northern part of Las Vegas.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Tran |first1=Edmond |title=The Crew 2 Review - On The Road Again |url=https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/the-crew-2-review-on-the-road-again/1900-6416936/ |website=GameSpot |accessdate=7 January 2019 |date=4 July 2018}}</ref>\n*The hotel, casino and tower was featured at the beginning of the 2016 film ''[[Sharknado: The 4th Awakens]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Scene In Nevada: Sharknado 4: The 4th Awakens |url=https://nevadafilm.com/scene-in-nevada-sharknado-4-the-4th-awakens/ |website=Nevada Film Office |accessdate=7 January 2019 |date=2 May 2018}}</ref>\n*The tower appears in the video game ''[[Gangstar Vegas]]''.\n\n==Gallery==\n<center>\n<gallery>\nFile:Stratosphere view from ground level.jpg|View looking upwards at the Stratosphere\nFile:Stratosphere las vegas.jpg|View from front\nFile:Stratosphere tower at night.jpg|View from ground, inverted image\nFile:Clouds over Stratosphere Las Vegas.jpg|Clouds over the Stratosphere at midday\nFile:05 Insanity the Ride 2.jpg|Insanity, the ride atop the tower\nFile:StratoXScream.jpg|The X-Scream on top of the Stratosphere \"drops\" riders over the edge of the tower\nFile:Stratosphere roller.jpg|View of the former High Roller ride\nFile:Stratosphere Las Vegas - November 2003.jpg|Aerial view of the Stratosphere\n</gallery>\n</center>\n\n==Notes==\n{{noteslist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book | last=Smith | first=John L. | title=No Limit: The Rise and Fall of Bob Stupak and Las Vegas' Stratosphere Tower | location=Las Vegas | publisher=Huntington Press | year=1997 | isbn=0-929712-18-8}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Stratosphere Las Vegas}}\n\n*{{Official website|1=http://www.thestrat.com}}\n*[http://www.pcap.com/strato3.htm Las Vegas Leisure Guide page on the Stratosphere, with construction details]\n*{{Structurae|id=20003279|title=Stratosphere Tower}}\n*[https://maps.google.com/maps?ll=36.147487,-115.156213&spn=0.005096,0.007918&t=k&hl=en Satellite shot]\n\n{{Las Vegas casinos}}\n{{Las Vegas hotels}}\n{{Las Vegas skyscrapers}}\n{{Las Vegas Strip}}\n{{Las Vegas Valley}}\n{{Supertall}}\n{{Golden Entertainment}}\n\n[[Category:Architecture of the Las Vegas Valley]]\n[[Category:Casino hotels]]\n[[Category:Casinos in the Las Vegas Valley]]\n[[Category:Golden Entertainment]]\n[[Category:Hotel buildings completed in 1996]]\n[[Category:Hotels established in 1996]]\n[[Category:Towers in Nevada]]\n[[Category:Las Vegas Strip]]\n[[Category:Observation towers in the United States]]\n[[Category:Resorts in the Las Vegas Valley]]\n[[Category:Skyscraper hotels in Las Vegas]]\n[[Category:Towers completed in 1996]]\n[[Category:Towers with revolving restaurants]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Hotel in Las Vegas}}\n{{Infobox building\n|name = The Strat Hotel, Casino and SkyPod\n|logo = Logo for The Strat hotel-casino.jpg\n|logo_caption = \n|image = Aerial view Casino Stratosphere LAS 09 2017 4912.jpg\n|caption = Stratosphere Tower in 2017\n|altitude =\n|cost={{US$|70 million}}\n|groundbreaking_date = November 5, 1991\n|start_date = February 1992\n|completion_date = \n|opened_date = April 30, 1996<ref name=\"STRAT emp\">{{cite web |url=https://www.emporis.com/buildings/122231/stratosphere-tower-las-vegas-nv-usa |title=Stratosphere Tower, Las Vegas |publisher=Emporis |accessdate=2017-01-15}}</ref><ref name=USA>{{citeweb |url=http://traveltips.usatoday.com/stratosphere-tower-3146.html |title=Facts about the Stratosphere Tower|publisher=USA Today |accessdate=2017-01-16}}</ref> \n|floor_area = \n|address = 2000 [[Las Vegas Boulevard]] South\n|location = [[Las Vegas]], [[Nevada]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n|room_count=\n|building_type = [[Observation tower]]\n|coordinates = {{Coord|36.147386|-115.155389|region:US-NV_type:landmark|display=inline,title}}\n|antenna_spire = {{Convert|1149|ft|1|abbr=on}}\n|floor_count = \n|status = Operating\n|est_completion = \n|architect = Ned Baldwin\n|developer = [[Bob Stupak]]\n|elevator_count = 7 (4 high speed double deck elevators, 3 local elevators in the pod)\n|main_contractor = \n|architecture_firm = \n|structural_engineer = \n|services_engineer = \n|civil_engineer = \n|url = \n|references = \n|module={{Infobox casino\n|embed=yes\n|name        = Other information\n|mapframe=no\n|rooms       = 2,427\n|theme =\n|date_opened = \n|space_gaming= {{convert|80000|sqft|abbr=on}}\n|attractions = {{hlist|[[Big Shot (ride)|Big Shot]]|[[Insanity (ride)|Insanity]]|[[X-Scream]]|Stratosphere Tower|[[SkyJump Las Vegas]]}}\n|shows       = \n|notable_restaurants = {{hlist|Top of the World|Fellini's Ristorante|Roxy's Diner|Lucky's}}\n|owner       = [[Golden Entertainment]]\n|casino_type = Land-based\n|renovations = 2000\u201301, 2010,<ref name=20-million>{{cite web |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/2011/jan/13/stratosphere-undergoes-20-million-renovation/ |title=Stratosphere undergoes $20 million renovation |publisher=Las Vegas Sun |accessdate=2017-01-15}}</ref> 2019\u20132020\n|names_pre   = Stratosphere\n|coordinates = \n|website     = {{URL|thestrat.com}}\n}}}}\n'''The Strat Hotel, Casino and SkyPod'''{{efn|Stylized as \"The STRAT\".<ref name=\"Press\" />}} (formerly the '''Stratosphere''') is a [[hotel]], [[casino]] and [[tower]] located on [[Las Vegas Boulevard]] just north of the [[Las Vegas Strip]] in [[Las Vegas]], [[Nevada]], United States. The Strat is owned and operated by [[Golden Entertainment]], which acquired the resort and three other properties from [[American Casino & Entertainment Properties]] for $850 million in 2017.<ref name=\"reviewjournal.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/business/casinos-gaming/golden-closes-on-850m-deal-for-stratosphere-3-other-casinos/|title=Golden closes on $850M deal for Stratosphere, 3 other casinos|date=23 October 2017|work=Las Vegas Review-Journal|accessdate=31 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe property's signature attraction is the {{convert|1149|ft|1|abbr=on}} Stratosphere Tower, the tallest [[List of tallest towers in the world|freestanding observation tower]] in the United States,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stratospherehotel.com/thrills/|title=- Big Shot Stratosphere Tower Rides|author=|year=2011|publisher=Las Vegas Amusement Parks|accessdate=12 January 2011}}</ref> and the second-tallest in the [[Western Hemisphere]], surpassed only by the [[CN Tower]] in [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]]. It is the tallest tower west of the Mississippi River<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stratospherehotel.com/content/download/587/4973/version/1/file/Dale_Tower.pdf|title=The Stratosphere Tower to Dim Lights in Honor of Seven-Time NASCAR Champion Dale Earnhardt|website=Stratospherehotel.com|format=PDF|accessdate=2016-03-12}}</ref> and also the [[List of tallest buildings in Las Vegas|tallest structure in Las Vegas]] and [[List of tallest buildings in Nevada|in the state of Nevada]].<ref name=\"STRAT emp\" /> The hotel is a separate building with 24 stories, 2,427 rooms and an {{convert|80000|sqft|abbr=on}} casino. The Strat is located within the city limits of Las Vegas, and is sometimes considered to be the northernmost resort on the Las Vegas Strip, which is not located within the city.<ref name=\"North\" /><ref name=\"Kat2019\">{{cite news|url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/entertainment/entertainment-columns/kats/the-new-strat-still-says-were-part-of-the-las-vegas-strip-1696101/|title=The new Strat still says, 'We're part of the Las Vegas Strip'|last=Katsilometes|first=John|date=2019-06-26|work=Las Vegas Review-Journal|accessdate=2019-07-26}}</ref>\n\nThe Stratosphere, a project by [[Bob Stupak]], began construction in 1991.<ref name=\"Breaks\" /> The project integrated portions of the former [[Vegas World]] hotel-casino, which Stupak opened on the site in 1979. The Stratosphere opened on April 30, 1996.<ref name=\"Rave\" /> In March 2018, Golden Entertainment announced plans for $140 million renovation of the Stratosphere that will be unveiled in three phases.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cdcgamingreports.com/golden-entertainment-unveils-140-million-plans-for-stratosphere-posted-fourth-quarter-loss/|title=Golden Entertainment unveils $140 million plans for Stratosphere, posted fourth-quarter loss|author=|date=|website=CDC Gaming Reports|accessdate=31 March 2018}}</ref> Golden Entertainment announced in February 2019 that the resort would be rebranded to The Strat Hotel, Casino and SkyPod.<ref name=\"Press\" /> The name change became official in January 2020.\n\n==History==\n{{Main|Vegas World}}\nIn 1974, [[Bob Stupak]] opened a small casino in [[Las Vegas]] known as Bob Stupak's World Famous Million-Dollar Historic Gambling Museum and Casino, located north of the [[Las Vegas Strip]] on land previously occupied by the Todkill/Bill Hayden [[Lincoln Motor Company|Lincoln]] [[Mercury (automobile)|Mercury]] Dealership.<ref name=\"Strip\">{{cite web|url=http://striplv.com/archives/19-articles/featured/517-the-men-who-made-las-vegas-bob-stupak-the-polish-maverick.html|title=The Men Who Made Las Vegas - Bob Stupak - The Polish Maverick|website=StripLV.com|year=2014|last=Craft|first=Byron|accessdate=2017-03-20}}</ref> The casino burned down two months later,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/8636642/the_daily_herald/|title=Museum-Casino Destroyed By Fire on Vegas 'Strip'|date=1974-05-22|work=[[Daily Herald (Utah)|Daily Herald]]|access-date=2017-03-20}}</ref> and Stupak subsequently opened his [[Vegas World]] hotel and casino on the same property in 1979.<ref name=May01/>\n\n===Conception===\nThe concept for the Stratosphere began as a plan by Stupak to construct a 1,012-foot (308.46 m) neon sign tower for Vegas World. In early October 1989, Stupak submitted plans to the city for the approval of the neon sign tower which would stand four times taller than the hotel. Later in the week, Stupak withdrew his plans to allow time for a revised version of the tower that would include an elevator leading up to an [[observation deck]]. Stupak, who wanted the tower to become a local landmark, said, \"What I'm trying to do for Las Vegas is what the [[Eiffel Tower]] did for [[Paris]], what the [[Empire State Building]] did for [[New York City|New York]], what the Seattle [[Space Needle]] did for [[Seattle]].\"<ref name=\"Landmark\">{{cite news|title=Stupak wants a landmark|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/9617823/reno_gazettejournal/|accessdate=2017-03-20|work=[[Reno Gazette-Journal]]|date=1989-10-07}}</ref><ref name=\"Sign\">{{cite news|title=Vegas council turns down sign ordinance|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/9617842/reno_gazettejournal/|accessdate=2017-03-20|work=Reno Gazette-Journal|date=1989-10-20}}</ref> Stupak's plans received widespread opposition,<ref name=Towers/> including from Las Vegas city staff, who drafted an [[Local ordinance|ordinance]] that would have limited signs to 35 feet in height.<ref name=Landmark/> The [[Las Vegas City Council]] rejected the ordinance, considering it to be a poorly drawn measure aimed specifically at stopping Stupak's project.<ref name=Sign/>\n\nIn February 1990, Stupak unveiled his revised plans for a $50 million, 1,012-foot observation tower with a top floor that would include a revolving restaurant and four penthouse suites.<ref>{{cite news|title=Revised plans unveiled|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/9617993/reno_gazettejournal/|accessdate=2017-03-20|work=Reno Gazette-Journal|date=1990-02-14}}</ref> In April 1990, the city council approved Stupak's tower, despite objections from the [[Federal Aviation Administration]] (FAA), which stated that it was 200 feet (61 m) too tall.<ref>{{cite news|title=Las Vegas approves tower|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/9618016/reno_gazettejournal/|accessdate=2017-03-20|work=Reno Gazette-Journal|date=1990-04-19}}</ref> [[Nellis Air Force Base]] also opposed the tower. Stupak later said that there were \"all sorts of people out there opposed\" to the tower, saying, \"If it wasn't for the courage of the council, it would have never been built.\"<ref name=May01/>\n\nIn October 1991, the city gave approval to the tower's base and shaft, while the pod atop the tower had yet to be approved. At the time, Stupak was trying to obtain financing for the now-$100 million project, and was also under investigation by gaming officials over allegations that he used [[Vegas World#Vacation packages|deceptive advertising]] to lure customers to Vegas World.<ref name=\"Daily\">{{cite web |last= |first= |title=Casino owner is given green light |url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/285778205/ |work=[[The Spectrum (Utah)|The Spectrum]] |date=1991-10-23 |accessdate=2019-02-08 |via=Newspapers.com|url-access=subscription }}</ref> The project was now planned to include the \"world's first indoor African lion's park,\"<ref name=Daily/> consisting of a jungle habitat to be located at the tower base.<ref name=Breaks/><ref>{{cite news|title=Circus Maximus|url=http://www.newsweek.com/circus-maximus-201700|accessdate=2017-03-20|work=[[Newsweek]]|date=1991-11-03}}</ref>\n\n[[Groundbreaking]] for the project, known as the Stratosphere Tower, took place on November 5, 1991.<ref name=Breaks/> The start of actual construction had yet to be announced for the tower, which was still opposed by the FAA.<ref name=\"Breaks\">{{cite web |last= |first= |title=Stupak breaks ground for tower project |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/9618463/reno_gazettejournal/ |work=Reno Gazette-Journal |date=1991-11-06 |accessdate=2019-02-08 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last= |first= |title=Vegas tower worries air official |url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/153161322/ |work=Reno Gazette-Journal |date=1991-10-26 |accessdate=2019-02-08 |via=Newspapers.com|url-access=subscription }}</ref> Originally, Stupak had envisioned an 1,800-foot tower, although the ultimate height was reduced to {{convert|1149|ft|abbr=on}} because of concerns from the FAA about possible interference with flights from the nearby [[McCarran International Airport]].<ref name=USA/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lasvegassun.com/news/2009/sep/25/bob-stupak-builder-stratosphere-and-vegas-world-di/ |title=Bob Stupak, builder of Stratosphere and Vegas World, dies at 67 |website=Las Vegas Sun |date= 2009-09-25 |accessdate=2016-03-12}}</ref> The tower was designed by architect Ned Baldwin, who also worked on the [[CN Tower]] in [[Toronto]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Carter|first=Geoff|title=Tourists For Breakfast: Designing Vegas|url=http://www.lasvegasweekly.com/2002/04_11/art_tfb.html|work=[[Las Vegas Weekly]]|date=April 2002|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020621082703/http://www.lasvegasweekly.com/2002/04_11/art_tfb.html|archivedate=2002-06-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Winsa |first=Patty |title=CN Tower built to last |url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/2014/02/23/cn_tower_built_to_last.html |accessdate=2019-07-18 |work=[[Toronto Star]] |date=2014-02-23}}</ref>\n\n===Construction===\n[[File:Western-towers.png|thumb|upright|\u2022 [[CN Tower]], Toronto<br />\u2022 [[Willis Tower]] (formerly Sears), Chicago<br />\u2022 Stratosphere, Las Vegas<br />\u2022 [[Space Needle]], Seattle]]\nConstruction of the $32 million tower began in February 1992, on property adjacent to Vegas World.<ref name=\"BattleCreek\">{{cite news|title=Fire engulfs observation tower|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/9618662/battle_creek_enquirer/|accessdate=2017-03-20|work=Associated Press|date=1993-08-30}}</ref> The tower was built directly north of the Las Vegas Strip<ref name=\"North\">{{cite web |title=Tower tries to stretch Strip boundary north of Sahara |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/1996/apr/26/tower-tries-to-stretch-strip-boundary-north-of-sah/ |work=Las Vegas Sun |date=1996-04-26 |accessdate=2019-02-08 }}</ref> and south of [[downtown Las Vegas]],<ref name=\"May01\">{{cite web|url=http://lasvegassun.com/news/2001/may/04/stupak-proud-but-not-notably-nostalgic-about-strat/|title=Stupak proud, but not notably nostalgic about Stratosphere|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=2001-05-04|accessdate=2019-02-08|first=Richard N.|last=Velotta}}</ref> in an area known as Meadows Village, a crime-ridden neighborhood nicknamed [[Naked City, Las Vegas|Naked City]].<ref name=\"Mean\">{{cite web |last=Zekan |first=Karen |title=Tower rises from mean streets |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/1996/apr/26/tower-rises-from-mean-streets/ |work=Las Vegas Sun |date=1996-04-26 |accessdate=2019-02-08 }}</ref> Shortly before its opening, a Stratosphere spokesman said, \"We hope Stratosphere will be the catalyst that spurs redevelopment\" in the area, while acknowledging, \"We plunked down a half-billion-dollar project in the middle of one of the worst neighborhoods.\"<ref name=Mean/>\n\nOn August 29, 1993, around midnight, hundreds of customers at Vegas World were evacuated when the half-finished tower caught on fire, during which no injuries occurred.<ref name=BattleCreek/><ref name=\"Rained\">{{cite web|author=Elizabeth Holland and Steve Sebelius |url=http://www.lasvegassun.com/news/1993/aug/30/tower-fire-rained-debris/ |title=Tower fire rained debris |website=Las Vegas Sun |date= 1993-08-30 |accessdate=2016-03-12}}</ref> The Stratosphere had been planned to open in August 1994, although the fire was expected to delay construction by eight weeks. Stupak said that the tower's first phase would still be ready in time with an accelerated construction schedule.<ref>{{cite news|title=Casino operator vows to finish building fire-damaged tower|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/9618683/reno_gazettejournal/|accessdate=2017-03-20|work=Reno Gazette-Journal|date=1993-09-03}}</ref> A large crane located atop the tower, used for construction, was also damaged in the fire.<ref name=Rained/><ref name=\"Winds\">{{cite news|title=Winds hamper tower work|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/9618706/reno_gazettejournal/|accessdate=2017-03-20|work=Reno Gazette-Journal|date=1993-09-13}}</ref> The following month, high winds prevented the scheduled dismantling of the crane, a process that was expected to take two days. At that time, the cause of the fire remained unknown.<ref name=Winds/> Following the fire,<ref name=Rave/> Stupak had trouble financing the completion of the tower.<ref name=May01/>\n\nTo continue construction,<ref name=Rave/> [[Grand Casinos]] announced plans in November 1993 to purchase 33 percent of the Stratosphere and Vegas World by acquiring shares in Stupak's Stratosphere Corporation.<ref>{{cite news|last=Marcotty|first=Josephine|title=Grand Casinos makes Vegas deal|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/9618745/star_tribune/|accessdate=2017-03-20|work=Star Tribune|date=1993-11-17}}</ref> Grand Casinos, owned by Stupak's poker friend [[Lyle Berman]], ultimately purchased a 43% stake in the resort.<ref name=Rave/> Vegas World closed on February 1, 1995, for remodeling in order to be integrated into the Stratosphere resort.<ref>{{cite news|title=Vacationers line up for World's last days|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/9619141/reno_gazettejournal/|accessdate=March 20, 2017|work=Reno Gazette-Journal|date=February 1, 1995}}</ref> Vegas World's two hotel towers,<ref name=RecNet/> consisting of 932 rooms,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://securities.stanford.edu/filings-documents/1002/GND96/001.html|title=Grand Casinos, Inc. Securities Litigation|publisher=Stanford University Law School|date=December 23, 1996|accessdate=May 23, 2015}}</ref> were renovated to become part of the Stratosphere.<ref name=\"RecNet\">{{cite web|url=http://www.recordnet.com/article/19950924/A_NEWS/309249984|title=Las Vegas reaches higher: 100-story roller coaster latest gamble for city|publisher=RecordNet.com|date=September 24, 1995|accessdate=May 23, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 1994, crews erected a crane \u2013 taller than the earlier one \u2013 that would allow them to continue work on the rising tower. The 75-ton crane stood 400 feet tall and was installed over the course of four days. Removal of the crane began in October 1995, with the use of a second crane. The dismantling of the crane was one of the most significant challenges for the people working on the tower. The unique design of the tower pod and its limit space required construction crews to carefully plan the installation of the second crane, which weighed 30 tons. The second crane would lower pieces of the original crane to the ground, and would then be used to lift a seven-ton [[derrick]] into place, allowing workers to carry down sections of the second crane. The derrick would then be disassembled by hand, and workers would use a construction elevator to bring down the pieces. The complex and risky process was expected to take nearly two months.<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |title=Workers dismantling crane |url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/477284277/ |work=Elko Daily Free Press |date=1995-10-11 |accessdate=2019-07-27 |via=Newspapers.com |url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nYears before the Stratosphere's opening, a three-block neighborhood of houses in Meadows Village was demolished to help make room for the resort's 4,500-space parking garage.<ref name=Mean/> In 1994,<ref name=LVS-Apr96/> officials from the Stratosphere project \u2013 located north of the [[Aztec Inn]] motel-casino<ref name=\"LVS2012\">{{cite web|url=http://lasvegassun.com/blogs/kats-report/2012/apr/06/new-and-improved-stratosphere-beacon-noble-risk-ta/|title=New-and-improved Stratosphere is a beacon of noble risk-taking|last=Katsilometes|first=John|date=2012-04-06|work=Las Vegas Sun|accessdate=2019-02-08}}</ref> \u2013 entered an agreement with the city's [[Las Vegas Redevelopment Agency]] to have the Aztec Inn's parking lot condemned through [[eminent domain]] and turned over to the Stratosphere.<ref name=\"LVS-Apr96\">{{cite web|url=http://lasvegassun.com/news/1996/apr/26/eminent-domain-redevelopment-issues-remain/|title=Eminent domain, redevelopment issues remain|last=Sebelius|first=Steve|date=1996-04-26|work=Las Vegas Sun|accessdate=2019-02-08}}</ref><ref name=\"LVRJ-Mar97\">{{cite web|url=http://www.lvrj.com/lvrj_home/1997/Mar-09-Sun-1997/news/4959608.html|title=They can fight city hall|last=Zapler|first=Mike|date=1997-03-09|work=[[Las Vegas Review-Journal]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19970719063545/http://www.lvrj.com/lvrj_home/1997/Mar-09-Sun-1997/news/4959608.html|archivedate=1997-07-19}}</ref> The agreement was opposed by the Aztec Inn,<ref name=LVS-Apr96/> and in 1995 was ruled by a judge to be unconstitutional.<ref name=LVRJ-Mar97/><ref name=LVS-Apr96/> By April 1996, the Aztec Inn settled with the Stratosphere and agreed to sell its parking lot.<ref name=LVS-Apr96/> Separately, the Stratosphere agreed to provide free rent and relocation expenses to approximately 140 residents in a nearby area of Meadows Village that was cleared for an eventual expansion of the resort.<ref>{{cite web |title=Residents Around Stratosphere Tower Evicted |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/1996/mar/19/residents-around-stratosphere-tower-evicted/ |work=Las Vegas Sun |date=1996-03-19 |accessdate=2019-02-08 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Sebelius |first=Steve |title=Evictions delayed for some Stratosphere neighbors |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/1996/mar/20/evictions-delayed-for-some-stratosphere-neighbors/ |work=Las Vegas Sun |date=1996-03-20 |accessdate=2019-02-08 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Residents near Stratosphere get aid |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/1996/mar/28/residents-near-stratosphere-get-aid/ |work=Las Vegas Sun |date=1996-03-28 |accessdate=2019-02-08 }}</ref><ref name=Mean/>\n\n[[File:T-240085515.jpg|thumb|right|Stratosphere pod during construction (September 1995)]]\nAfter a 1995 motorcycle accident that left Stupak in a [[coma]] for 12 days, he said that the controversy and \"all the complaining\" about the tower stopped: \"There were people who didn't like the tower, this and that, but after the accident, it was like nobody had anything negative to say about it.\"<ref name=May01/> As construction of the resort neared completion, one of the rides being planned for the resort was a giant ape that would carry riders up and down on one of the tower's columns.<ref>{{cite news|last=Dretzka|first=Gary|title=Vegas tower topped by roller coaster|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/9619227/south_florida_sun_sentinel/|accessdate=2017-03-20|work=Chicago Tribune|date=1996-01-28}}</ref> The ride was delayed in 1996,<ref>{{cite news |last=Schumacher |first=Geoff |title=King Kong delayed |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/1996/may/24/king-kong-delayed/ |accessdate=2019-02-09 |work=Las Vegas Sun |date=1996-05-24}}</ref> and ultimately cancelled.\n\nIn March 1996, the [[Nevada Gaming Control Board]] approved Stupak, the chairman of Stratosphere Corporation, for a [[gaming license]], along with other company individuals. Stupak owned 17 percent of Stratosphere Corporation, while Grand Casinos owned 43 percent. Stupak was one of nine directors in the company, and would not oversee daily operations of the company.<ref name=\"Problem\">{{cite web |last=Thompson |first=Gary |title=Gaming license no problem for Stupak |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/1996/mar/07/gaming-license-no-problem-for-stupak/ |work=Las Vegas Sun |date=1996-03-07 |accessdate=2019-02-08 }}</ref> The resort was expected to employ a total of 3,000 people, and began hiring for the remaining 2,400 employees in March 1996, a month before the opening. At the time, Stupak said he may resign his chairman position as soon as a month after the resort's opening, in order to pursue other projects.<ref>{{cite web |title=Commission gives final OK to Stratosphere plan |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/1996/mar/22/commission-gives-final-ok-to-stratosphere-plan/ |work=Las Vegas Sun |date=1996-03-22 |accessdate=2019-02-08 }}</ref>\n\nShortly before its opening, several [[Stunt performer|daredevil]]s had expressed an interest in performing stunts from the top of the tower, but they were declined for safety reasons.<ref name=\"Build\">{{cite web |title=Columnist: Build it and they will come |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/1996/apr/26/columnist-build-it-and-they-will-come/ |work=Las Vegas Sun |date=1996-04-26 |accessdate=2019-02-08 }}</ref> Smoke in the tower's pod restaurant forced an evacuation of workers on April 25, 1996, days before the opening. The smoke originated from the pod's fifth-floor kitchen, one floor above the restaurant, due to a faulty ventilator in the air-flow duct system. The pod contained four tanks with 32,000 gallons of water for firefighters in the event of a fire, but they were not needed.<ref>{{cite web |last=Scott |first=Cathy |title=Smoke, but no towering inferno |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/1996/apr/26/smoke-but-no-towering-inferno/ |work=Las Vegas Sun |date=1996-04-26 |accessdate=2019-02-08 }}</ref>\n\n===Opening===\nA film crew followed Stupak all day leading up to the opening.<ref name=May01/> More than 8,000 [[VIP]] guests visited the resort for a premiere party on the night of April 29, 1996, hours before its midnight opening. Stupak attended the event with singer [[Phyllis McGuire]]. Other attendees included Nevada governor [[Bob Miller (Nevada governor)|Bob Miller]] and Las Vegas mayor [[Jan Laverty Jones]].<ref name=Rave/><ref name=Silences/><ref>{{cite news |last=Shemeligian |first=Bob |title=Tower debut shaky if you didn't speak Stratosphere |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/1996/may/03/bob-sheneligian-tower-debut-shaky-if-you-didnt-spe/ |accessdate=2019-02-09 |work=Las Vegas Sun |date=1996-05-03}}</ref> Media from around the world also attended the event,<ref name=May01/> which was broadcast live by [[CNBC]] as well as television stations in Las Vegas and Los Angeles.<ref name=Rave/> A six-minute fireworks show, costing $50,000, began at 10:30&nbsp;p.m.<ref name=\"Rave\">{{cite web |last=Thompson |first=Gary |title=Tower draws rave reviews |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/1996/apr/30/tower-draws-rave-reviews/ |work=Las Vegas Sun |date=1996-04-30 |accessdate=2019-02-08 }}</ref><ref name=Silences/> Doors in the tower's pod had been left partially open to accommodate television camera cables, and smoke from the fireworks filled the pod and set off fire alarms, resulting in the shutdown of elevators and stranding hundreds of VIP guests.<ref>{{cite web |title=Smoke strands guests atop tower |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/1996/may/01/smoke-strands-guests-atop-tower/ |work=Las Vegas Sun |date=1996-05-01 |accessdate=2019-02-08 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Thompson |first=Gary |title=Bugs bedevil Stratosphere |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/1996/may/03/bugs-bedevil-stratosphere/ |work=Las Vegas Sun |date=1996-05-03 |accessdate=2019-02-09 }}</ref>\n\nThe $550 million complex featured {{convert|354000|sqft|abbr=on}},<ref name=Towers/> including {{convert|140000|sqft|abbr=on}} of entertainment and shopping space.<ref name=\"SF\">{{cite news |last=Robins |first=Cynthia |title=Las Vegas' Stratosphere is fit for the intrepid |url=https://www.sfgate.com/travel/article/Las-Vegas-Stratosphere-is-fit-for-the-intrepid-3142441.php |accessdate=2019-02-09 |work=SFGate |date=1996-05-26}}</ref> A {{convert|97000|sqft|abbr=on}} casino was part of the resort's first phase, which also included 1,500 hotel rooms. The hotel portion was expected to open on May 7, 1996.<ref name=\"Towers\">{{cite web |last=Thompson |first=Gary |title=New landmark towers over Las Vegas |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/1996/apr/26/new-landmark-towers-over-las-vegas/ |work=Las Vegas Sun |date=1996-04-26 |accessdate=2019-02-08 }}</ref> An additional 1,000 hotel rooms were expected to be finished in November 1996.<ref>{{cite web |title=Hospitality Network adds Stratosphere to its list |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/1996/feb/23/hospitality-network-adds-stratosphere-to-its-list/ |work=Las Vegas Sun |date=1996-02-23 |accessdate=2019-02-08 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Stratosphere by night.jpg|thumb|upright|right|The Stratosphere pod and needle at night.]]\nThe resort had 3,100 employees.<ref name=Rave/> The casino featured 2,600 slot machines, and was decorated with a [[world's fair]] theme and bright colors.<ref name=SF/> The casino was divided into three sections, each with their own international theme.<ref>{{cite news |last=Welling |first=Stacey |title=Topping 1,149 feet, $550-million Stratosphere shoots for the sky |url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/159062248/ |work=Los Angeles Times |date=1996-06-23 |accessdate=2019-07-27 |via=Newspapers.com |url-access=subscription}}</ref> The hotel included a bronze statue of Stupak, which he disliked and never approved, saying, \"They spent $100,000 more for that statue than I spent to open my first place in 1974.\"<ref name=May01/> Another statue, in the center of the casino, featured a couple riding a dolphin set upon a bronze globe.<ref name=SF/>\n\nThe tower cost $70 million to construct.<ref name=Mean/> The tower's pod contains 12 stories and has one and a half miles of criss-crossed [[fiber-optic cable]] with lights which alternate between eight different colors.<ref>{{cite web |last=Calkins |first=Alison |title=Diamond image helped designer see the light |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/1996/apr/26/diamond-image-helped-designer-see-the-light/ |work=Las Vegas Sun |date=1996-04-26 |accessdate=2019-02-08 }}</ref> A 149-foot needle<ref name=SF/> located on top of the pod consists of a five-square-foot steel-beam frame with an internal ladder. Atop the needle frame are two four-inch beams which are laid out horizontally to form an \"X\".<ref name=Build/> The observation deck rises 872 feet.<ref name=Figures/> The pod included two concrete-banded bunker floors, located beneath its three wedding chapels, for use in the event of an emergency.<ref name=SF/> Stupak's critics did not believe he would be able to complete the tower, in part because of his controversial promotional tactics at Vegas World.<ref name=Towers/><ref name=\"Silences\">{{cite web |last=German |first=Jeff |title=Stupak silences his critics with Stratosphere's opening |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/1996/apr/30/jeff-german-stupak-silences-his-critics-with-strat/ |work=Las Vegas Sun |date=1996-04-30 |accessdate=2019-02-08 }}</ref>\n\nAlthough the resort is located north of the Las Vegas Strip, it advertised itself as being on the Strip, with the slogan, \"We define the top of the Strip.\"<ref name=North/> The Stratosphere was projected to attract at least 5.5 million visitors in its first year.<ref name=\"Figures\">{{cite web |last=Thompson |first=Gary |title=It's not tallest, but tower figures to pile up revenue |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/1996/apr/26/its-not-tallest-but-tower-figures-to-pile-up-reven/ |work=Las Vegas Sun |date=1996-04-26 |accessdate=2019-02-08 }}</ref> Around the time of its opening, financial analysts were optimistic of the resort's future.<ref name=Towers/> Revenue for the first five weeks was lower than expected. Stratosphere Corporation attributed the low results to the resort being partly unfinished, and said it would borrow $48.5 million from Grand Casinos to finance enhancements to the property, including the completion of the 1,000 additional rooms, and the opening of unfinished retail shops.<ref>{{cite web |title=Stratosphere revenues less than predicted |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/1996/jun/07/stratosphere-revenues-less-than-predicted/ |work=Las Vegas Sun |date=1996-06-07 |accessdate=2019-02-08 }}</ref> The resort continued to suffer financially.<ref name=May01/><ref>{{cite news |last=Thompson |first=Gary |title=Troubles loom at Stratosphere |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/1996/jul/23/troubles-loom-at-stratosphere/ |accessdate=2019-07-27 |work=Las Vegas Sun |date=1996-07-23}}</ref>\n\n===Carl Icahn ownership===\n[[File:The Stratosphere Tower, Las Vegas, Nevada.jpg|thumb|Looking up from the base of the Stratosphere Tower, with the X-Scream ride hanging over the edge in 2009]]\nStupak, who had already made plans to move on to other projects,<ref name=Silences/> resigned as chairman less than three months after the opening, leaving Berman in charge. Stupak's statue was subsequently removed from the property.<ref name=May01/> The resort's second phase was halted in August 1996, due to financial problems;<ref name=\"Halts\">{{cite news |title=Stratosphere halts growth |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/1996/aug/30/stratosphere-halts-growth/ |work=Las Vegas Sun |date=1996-08-30 |accessdate=2019-07-27}}</ref> the additional hotel building consisted of an unfinished, 15-story structure of concrete and [[rebar]].<ref name=Retailers/> Berman intended to make the resort profitable, but ultimately declared bankruptcy in January 1997.<ref name=May01/> Stupak had previously called Berman \"the best casino operator in the world,\"<ref name=Problem/> but later said about Grand Casinos' operation of the resort, \"They just weren't up to it.\"<ref name=May01/>\n\n[[Carl Icahn]] planned to purchase the bankrupt resort. In mid-1997, Stupak made a plan to regain control of the Stratosphere by producing a half-hour video criticizing Grand Casinos' board members. Stupak also considered developing a bankruptcy plan of his own to compete against Icahn and Grand Casinos. Ultimately, Stupak's video never aired on local television as scheduled,<ref name=May01/> and Icahn gained control of the property in 1998.<ref name=Second/> In the years after Icahn took over, Stupak sometimes visited the Stratosphere's Top of the World restaurant but was otherwise disinterested in the resort. In 2001, Stupak stated that he felt prouder when he opened his earlier casinos on the site in 1974 and 1979. Stupak stated his biggest disappointment with the Stratosphere was not being able to have it built to his initially planned 1,800-foot height.<ref name=May01/>\n\nThe second hotel tower, with 24 stories, was [[Topping out|topped off]] on November 2, 2000.<ref name=\"Second\">{{cite news |title=Second tower at Stratosphere topped off |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/2000/nov/03/second-tower-at-stratosphere-topped-off/ |accessdate=2019-02-09 |work=Las Vegas Sun |date=2000-11-03}}</ref> The $65 million project included 1,002 rooms, a {{convert|67000|sqft|abbr=on}} pool and recreation area, and a coffee shop. Excluding the new tower, the hotel had 1,444 rooms. The new project was meant to improve business at the casino and its retail mall, the Tower Shops.<ref>{{cite news |title=Second Stratosphere tower topped off; to open next year |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/2000/nov/06/second-stratosphere-tower-topped-off-to-open-next-/ |accessdate=2019-02-09 |work=Las Vegas S |date=2000-11-06}}</ref> A major addition was completed in June 2001 for $1 billion that included finishing the second hotel tower.\n\n[[File:Stratosphere Las Vegas logo.svg|thumb|right|Stratosphere logo until 2019]]\nIn the early 2000s, the company attempted to get approval for a roller coaster that would run from several hundred feet up the tower and, in the last proposal, across [[Las Vegas Boulevard]]. Part of that last proposal included an entry monument on the ride over Las Vegas Boulevard welcoming people to the City of Las Vegas. The Las Vegas City Council did not approve the project due to objections from the neighbors over possible noise from the enclosed cars on the proposed ride.{{citation needed|date=February 2019}} Five people have committed suicide by jumping from the tower's observation area, between 2000 and 2007.<ref>{{cite news |last=Radke |first=Jace |title=Man jumps from Stratosphere Tower |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/2000/jan/07/man-jumps-from-stratosphere-tower/ |accessdate=2019-02-09 |work=Las Vegas Sun |date=2000-01-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Boy, 16, jumps from Stratosphere |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/2002/jul/15/boy-16-jumps-from-stratosphere/ |accessdate=2019-02-09 |work=Las Vegas Sun |date=2002-07-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Clarke |first=Norm |title=Tragedy follows 'Elvis' show work |url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/lvrj_home/2005/Mar-30-Wed-2005/news/26180561.html |work=Las Vegas Review-Journal |date=2005-03-30 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051130013343/http://www.reviewjournal.com/lvrj_home/2005/Mar-30-Wed-2005/news/26180561.html |archivedate=2005-11-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Stratosphere Jump: Investigation confirms woman killed herself |url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/lvrj_home/2005/Apr-13-Wed-2005/news/26280890.html |work=Las Vegas Review-Journal |date=2005-04-13 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051130010319/http://www.reviewjournal.com/lvrj_home/2005/Apr-13-Wed-2005/news/26280890.html |archivedate=2005-11-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Man jumps from Stratosphere tower |url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/lvrj_home/2006/Feb-08-Wed-2006/news/5774712.html |work=Las Vegas Review-Journal |date=2006-02-08 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070701202058/http://www.reviewjournal.com/lvrj_home/2006/Feb-08-Wed-2006/news/5774712.html |archivedate=2007-07-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Man killed in jump from Stratosphere |url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/news/in-brief-3294/ |work=Las Vegas Review-Journal |date=2007-05-07 |accessdate=2019-02-09}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2010, [[American Casino & Entertainment Properties]] announced a new thrill ride for the top of the tower: SkyJump, a controlled-descent, [[bungee jumping]]\u2013like ride that would allow riders to plummet {{convert|855|ft|m}} attached to a high-speed descent wire. It opened on April 20, 2010.<ref name=\"aaavegas1\">{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.aaavegas.com/attractions/the-stratosphere-las-vegas-hotel-casino-to-add-worlds-highest-skyjump%E2%80%9D-to-their-collection-of-thrills/2010/01/11 |title=The Stratosphere Las Vegas Hotel & Casino To Add World's Highest \"Skyjump\" To Their Collection Of Thrills &#124; AccessVegas.com Las Vegas News |website=Aaavegas.com |date=2013-01-24 |accessdate=2016-03-12}}</ref>\n\n[[File:The Stratosphere Las Vegas 2 Bay FM Antenna.jpg|thumb|right|upright|KOAS-FM1 and KVGS-FM1 transmitting antenna atop the Stratosphere, 2010.]]\nRadio stations [[KOAS|KOAS 105.7 (FM)]] and [[KVGS|KVGS 107.9 (FM)]] have on-channel FM boosters broadcasting from an antenna at the top of the tower's structure. Licensed as KOAS-FM1 and KVGS-FM1, they are the only radio stations with transmitters at the tower. However, the signals being transmitted from this structure are relatively low-power and only cover the immediate Las Vegas area on a \"fill in\" or \"booster\" basis. Both of these stations have their main transmitter sites located elsewhere, and those transmitter sites are what give these stations more widespread regional coverage.\n\nBeginning in 2010, the Stratosphere renovated several areas of the property. As part of a $20 million renovation plan, improvements were made to many hotel rooms, the casino, and the main entrance area. Improvements and upgrades have also been made in the Top of the World Restaurant and Level 107 lounge.<ref name=20-million/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/business/skyjump-renovations-seen-boost-stratosphere-parent |title=SkyJump, renovations seen as boost for Stratosphere parent |website=Las Vegas Review-Journal |date=2010-05-12 |accessdate=2016-03-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.vegaschatter.com/story/2011/1/14/92236/5315/vegas-travel/The+Stratosphere+Has+Pretty+New+Rooms+with+a+View+of+the+Fontaine-Bust |title=Things To Do In Las Vegas - Attractions & Travel Guide - Cond\u00e9 Nast Traveler |website=Vegaschatter.com |date= |accessdate=2016-03-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Sylvester |first=Ron |url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/765567867/Stratosphere-renovations-give-Vegas-icon-new-mojo.html?pg=all |title=Stratosphere renovations give Vegas icon new mojo |publisher=Deseret News |date=2012-04-11 |accessdate=2016-03-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Warren Mason |url=http://mylifemagazine.com/the-new-stratosphere |title=The 'New' Stratosphere |website=Mylifemagazine.com |date= |accessdate=2016-03-12}}</ref>\n\n===Golden Entertainment===\nIn June 2017, [[Golden Entertainment]] agreed to purchase American Casino & Entertainment Properties.<ref>{{cite news|title=Iconic Stratosphere casino in Las Vegas changes hands|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/iconic-stratosphere-casino-in-las-vegas-changes-hands/2017/06/12/e53e3f58-4fa2-11e7-b74e-0d2785d3083d_story.html|accessdate=2017-06-12|work=The Washington Post|agency=Associated Press|date=2017-06-22}}</ref> Golden Entertainment's $850 million purchase of the company, including the Stratosphere, was completed in October 2017.<ref name=\"reviewjournal.com\"/>\n\nIn March 2018, Golden Entertainment announced plans for a $140 million renovation of the Stratosphere that will be completed over three phases.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/business/casinos-gaming/golden-entertainment-to-invest-140m-in-stratosphere/|title=Golden Entertainment to invest $140M in Stratosphere|author=|date=15 March 2018|website=Las Vegas Review-Journal|accessdate=31 March 2018}}</ref> On February 1, 2019, plans were announced to rename the resort as The STRAT Hotel, Casino and SkyPod.<ref name=\"Press\">{{cite web |title=Golden Entertainment, Inc. Announces Stratosphere Rebrand to 'The STRAT' |url=https://www.stratospherehotel.com/Flyers/Press/2019-Press-Releases/Golden-Entertainment-Inc.-Announces-Stratosphere-Rebrand-to-The-STRAT |publisher=Golden Entertainment |accessdate=2019-02-09 |date=2019-02-04|quote=On Sunday, Feb. 3, the Stratosphere, Casino, Hotel & Tower began its transition to The STRAT Hotel, Casino and SkyPod [\u2026].}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Prince |first=Todd |title=Stratosphere in Las Vegas to rebrand to The STRAT |url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/business/casinos-gaming/stratosphere-in-las-vegas-to-rebrand-to-the-strat-1587571/ |accessdate=February 2, 2019 |work=Las Vegas Review-Journal |date=February 1, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Philly\">{{cite news |title=Stratosphere casino-hotel in Las Vegas to be renamed |url=http://www.philly.com/news/nation-world/stratosphere-vegas-the-strat-casino-skypod-20190202.html |accessdate=February 2, 2019 |work=[[Philly.com]] |agency=Associated Press |date=February 1, 2019}}</ref> For years, \"The Strat\" had been used by local residents as a nickname.<ref>{{cite news |last=Radke |first=Brock |title=The Stratosphere is rebranding to the STRAT |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/2019/feb/02/stratosphere-rebranding-the-strat/ |accessdate=2019-02-09 |work=Las Vegas Sun |date=2019-02-02}}</ref> The transition to The Strat began with two commercials aired locally two days later during [[Super Bowl LIII]].<ref name=Philly/><ref name=\"Klas\">{{cite news |last=Hopkins |first=Justin |title=Goodbye Stratosphere, hello Strat |url=https://www.lasvegasnow.com/news/local-news/goodbye-stratosphere-hello-strat/1761737195 |accessdate=2019-02-09 |work=KLAS-TV |date=2019-02-07}}</ref> The name change would become official at a later date.<ref name=Klas/>\n\nA three-piece statue, created by local artists, was installed at the resort's front entrance in April 2019. The statue consists of three stainless steel figures staring at the tower. They range in height from 9 to 15 feet, with the tallest one pointing at the tower. [[Blake Sartini]], the chairman and CEO of Golden Entertainment, said the statue was a symbol of the resort's new branding. He also said, \"We wanted to create a piece that people would use as a 'wow' moment, an [[Instagram]] moment.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Karel |first=Janna |title='Look!' Strat installs local art piece on Las Vegas Boulevard |url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/entertainment/arts-culture/look-strat-installs-local-art-piece-on-las-vegas-boulevard-1644501/ |accessdate=2019-12-06 |work=Las Vegas Review-Journal |date=2019-04-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Seeman |first=Matthew |title=New sculpture unveiled outside entrance to The STRAT |url=https://news3lv.com/news/local/new-sculpture-unveiled-outside-entrance-to-the-strat |accessdate=2019-12-06 |work=KSNV |date=2019-04-19}}</ref> Two areas for live entertainment \u2013 one on the casino floor and one in the former space of a lounge \u2013 were being added in June 2019,<ref name=Kat2019/> as well as a new slot machine lounge.<ref name=\"Schulz\">{{cite news |last=Schulz |first=Bailey |title=STRAT updates bring competition for north Las Vegas Strip, analysts say |url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/business/strat-updates-bring-competition-for-north-las-vegas-strip-analysts-say-1760495/ |accessdate=2019-07-27 |work=Las Vegas Review-Journal |date=2019-07-19}}</ref> A glass walkway looking down 109 floors was expected to be complete by late 2020, along with the modernization and refurbishment of approximately 1,000 rooms.<ref name=Kat2019/> \"STRAT\" signage was installed in August 2019,<ref>{{cite news |title=Hooters Hotel sold, Strat new marquee on display |url=https://www.8newsnow.com/news/local-news/hooters-hotel-sold-strat-new-marquee-on-display/ |accessdate=2019-08-27 |work=KLAS |date=2019-08-26 |at=1:15}}</ref> and renovations on the south end of the casino floor were completed that year.<ref>{{cite news |last=Horwath |first=Bryan |title=New Strat boss has high hopes for property's new vibe, north Strip |url=https://vegasinc.lasvegassun.com/business/gaming/2019/nov/20/former-caesars-exec-hopes-stickiness-strat-leads/ |accessdate=2019-11-30 |work=VegasInc |date=2019-11-20}}</ref> Other renovations have included the resort's exterior and landscaping.<ref name=Velotta>{{cite news |last=Velotta |first=Richard N. |title=Golden Entertainment hopes renovations of The Strat boost earnings |url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/business/casinos-gaming/golden-entertainment-hopes-renovations-of-the-strat-boost-earnings-1887936/ |accessdate=2019-11-30 |work=Las Vegas Review-Journal |date=2019-11-07}}</ref> The Strat also installed [[Unmanned aerial vehicle|drone]] detection technology, alerting the property whenever illegal drones are flown near the tower.<ref>{{cite news |last=Pretty |first=Ted |title=The Strat uses new drone detection technology on Las Vegas Strip |url=https://www.fox5vegas.com/news/local/the-strat-uses-new-drone-detection-technology-on-las-vegas/article_8817f640-00d3-11ea-98db-171fe42e7cdb.html |accessdate=2019-11-30 |work=KVVU |date=2019-11-13}}</ref>\n\nThe resort was officially renamed The Strat Hotel, Casino and SkyPod during a celebration held on January 22, 2020. Among the attendees to the event were Nevada governor [[Steve Sisolak]], congresswoman [[Dina Titus]], [[Sammy Hagar]], [[Guy Fieri]], and [[Rick Springfield]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Sammy Hagar, Rick Springfield celebrate reinvention of The STRAT |url=https://www.ktnv.com/positivelylv/rock-icon-sammy-hagar-and-rick-springfield-celebrate-reinvention-of-the-strat |accessdate=2020-01-24 |work=KTNV |date=2020-01-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Miller |first=Cody |title=Sammy Hagar, Rick Springfield join Governor Sisolak for reopening of The STRAT |url=https://news3lv.com/news/local/sammy-hagar-rick-springfield-join-governor-sisolak-for-reopening-of-the-strat |accessdate=2020-01-24 |work=KSNV |date=2020-01-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Mancini |first=Al |title=Sammy Hagar to be guest bartender at The Strat on Jan. 22 |url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/entertainment/food/sammy-hagar-to-be-guest-bartender-at-the-strat-on-jan-22-1932810/ |accessdate=2020-01-24 |work=Las Vegas Review-Journal |date=2020-01-10}}</ref> Renovations were largely finished at the time, with the exception of a self-check-in area and remodeling that was scheduled to begin on the casino's north side during the second quarter of 2020. Half of the resort's 2,472 hotel rooms had been remodeled, and future renovations would also take place on the remaining rooms. The {{convert|80000|sqft|abbr=on}} casino, considered dark before, was remodeled with a new color scheme and an open layout. A new [[William Hill (bookmaker)|William Hill]] sports book was also added.<ref name=Schulz2>{{cite news |last=Schulz |first=Bailey |title=Strat's $100M renovation project nears completion |url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/business/casinos-gaming/strats-100m-renovation-project-nears-completion-1940283/ |accessdate=2020-01-14 |work=Las Vegas Review-Journal |date=2020-01-21}}</ref> The renovations, including four new restaurants, were designed to retain customers who usually only visited the pod area.<ref name=Klas/><ref name=Schulz2/> The renovation was also intended to help the property compete against nearby rivals, including upcoming resorts \u2013 [[The Drew Las Vegas|The Drew]] and [[Resorts World Las Vegas|Resorts World]] \u2013 as well as the renovated [[Sahara Las Vegas|Sahara]].<ref name=Schulz/>\n\n==Attractions and entertainment==\n[[File:Stratosphere Las Vegas -8Sept2008.jpg|upright|thumb|View from the top of the Stratosphere Tower in 2008]]\nThe top of the tower has two [[observation deck]]s, a [[revolving restaurant]] known as \"Top of the World\", and four thrill rides.\n\nAn indoor observation deck is located on the 108th floor, and includes food and beverage outlets, while stairs lead up to the outdoor deck on the 109th floor. Both decks provide wraparound views of the [[Las Vegas Valley]]. The indoor deck was remodeled and unveiled in July 2019.<ref name=\"KTNV\">{{cite news |last=Dinant |first=Jason |title=Remodeled STRAT observation deck debuts |url=https://www.ktnv.com/positivelylv/dining-and-entertainment/remodeled-strat-observation-deck-debuts |accessdate=2019-07-26 |work=KTNV |date=2019-07-22}}</ref>\n\n===Rides===\nRides at the Stratosphere include:\n*[[Big Shot (ride)|Big Shot]] at {{convert|1081|ft|abbr=on}} was the highest [[Amusement ride|thrill ride]] in the world until the Sky Drop opened on the [[Canton Tower]] at {{convert|1591|ft|abbr=on}}.\n*[[Insanity (ride)|Insanity]], opened in 2005, at {{convert|900|ft|abbr=on}} is the third highest thrill ride in the world; it dangles riders over the edge of the tower and then spins in a circular pattern at approximately forty miles per hour.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vegas.com/attractions/on-the-strip/stratosphere-insanity/ |website=www.vegas.com |title=Stratosphere insanity|accessdate=7 January 2019}}</ref> In a 2005 incident, riders were left dangling several hundred feet above the Las Vegas Strip for nearly an hour and a half when Insanity shut down; it was programmed to cease operation if a fault or problem is detected by the ride's control system.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/lvrj_home/2005/Apr-21-Thu-2005/news/26341046.html |last=Rogers |first=Keith |title=Teen, cousin suffer night of Insanity |website=Las Vegas Review-Journal |date=2005-04-21 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050423181225/http://www.reviewjournal.com/lvrj_home/2005/Apr-21-Thu-2005/news/26341046.html |archivedate=2005-04-23}}</ref>\n*[[SkyJump Las Vegas]], a controlled-descent, Bungee-jumping-like ride that allows riders to plummet {{convert|855|ft|abbr=on}} attached to a high-speed descent wire.<ref name=\"aaavegas1\"/> SkyJump opened on April 20, 2010.<ref>{{cite news |last=Winder |first=Carl |title=He's Sky Master at the Vegas Stratosphere: 'I throw people off' |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2013/may/18/nation/la-na-nn-sky-master-las-vegas-stratosphere-20130517 |accessdate=2019-02-09 |work=Los Angeles Times |date=2013-05-18}}</ref>\n*[[X-Scream]] at {{convert|866|ft|abbr=on}} is the fourth highest thrill ride in the world. It consists of a single car that rolls back and forth on a straight piece of track that slightly overhangs the tower and pivots vertically in a [[see-saw]] motion.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stratospherehotel.com/ThrillRides/X-Scream|title=X-Scream|website=Stratosphere Hotel Tower and Casino|language=en|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref>\n\nA previous ride, the [[High Roller (Stratosphere)|High Roller]], closed on December 30, 2005, and was dismantled.<ref name=LVM/> At {{convert|909|ft|abbr=on}}<ref>{{cite web|author=Stratosphere Hotel Las Vegas |url=http://www.lasvegastourism.com/stratosp.htm |title=Stratosphere Las Vegas, Official Site |website=Lasvegastourism.com |date= |accessdate=2016-03-12}}</ref> it was the second highest ride in the world and the highest [[roller coaster]].<ref name=\"LVM\">{{cite web|author= |url=http://lasvegasmagazine.com/entertainment/2014/apr/25/9-views-las-vegas/#/0 |title=9 Views of Las Vegas to Soak In |publisher=Las Vegas Magazine |date=2014-04-25 |accessdate=2016-03-12}}</ref>\n\n===Tower Shops===\nThe Tower Shops is a mall on the second level. The elevators that lead up to the observation decks are only accessible in the mall.<ref name=Rising/> [[Edward J. DeBartolo Sr.|DeBartolo Realty Corporation]], which owned a 50-percent interest in the Tower Shops, was acquired by [[Simon Property Group]] in March 1996, forming Simon DeBartolo Group.<ref name=Retailers/> The Tower Shops were a joint venture between Simon DeBartolo Group and Gordon Group, under the name Strato-Retail.<ref name=\"Headache\">{{cite news |last=Strow |first=David |title=Icahn hopes to ease resort's mall headache by buying it |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/2000/sep/25/icahn-hopes-to-ease-resorts-mall-headache-by-buyin/ |work=Las Vegas Sun |date=2000-09-25 |accessdate=2019-07-27}}</ref> The Stratosphere leased the retail space to Strato-Retail, which then [[sublease]]d it to retail tenants.<ref name=Sued/>\n\nWhen the Stratosphere opened in April 1996, its retail area was still largely under construction and consisted only of vendor carts spread across three areas with their own theme: Chinese, French, and Manhattan.<ref name=SF/> The mall was built by Missouri construction company McCarthy, which was finishing the first phase in May 1996.<ref name=\"Rising\">{{cite news |title=McCarthy's Big Vegas Project Rising To Stratosphere |url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/142523619/ |accessdate=2019-07-26 |work=St. Louis Post-Dispatch |date=1996-05-27 |via=Newspapers.com |url-access=subscription}}</ref> The next phase of the Tower Shops was halted in August 1996,<ref name=Halts/><ref>{{cite web |last= |first= |title=The Sky was the Limit//The Stratosphere's Tower Shops Reached for the Stars, Literally and Financially, but Have Failed to Fulfill Expectations |url=https://nl.newsbank.com |website=St. Paul Pioneer Press |accessdate=2019-07-27 |date=1996-09-27 |url-access=subscription |via=NewsLibrary}}</ref> leaving the mall with {{convert|69000|sqft|abbr=on}} of retail space.<ref name=NewShops/><ref name=Headache/> The second phase, scheduled for completion in December 1996, would have increased the mall to {{convert|160000|sqft|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |title=Stratosphere opens grand tower, resort |url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/159256112/ |work=Los Angeles Times |date=1996-04-07 |accessdate=2019-07-27 |via=Newspapers.com |url-access=subscription}}</ref> The second phase would have included a [[Rainforest Cafe]] as its main [[anchor tenant]].<ref name=Retailers/><ref name=Headache/> A Kids Quest child-care center was also planned as part of the second phase.<ref>{{cite web |last=Calkins |first=Alison |title=Tower has a place just for kids |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/1996/apr/26/tower-has-a-place-just-for-kids/ |work=Las Vegas Sun |date=1996-04-26 |accessdate=2019-02-08 }}</ref><ref name=Retailers/> As of February 1997, the mall had 32 of 45 stores opened, with the remainder expected to be open by the end of the second quarter. The mall had approximately 300 employees.<ref name=\"NewShops\">{{cite web |last=Caruso |first=Monica |title=Stratosphere continues to open new shops |url=http://www.lvrj.com/lvrj_home/1997/Feb-14-Fri-1997/business/4863616.html |work=Las Vegas Review-Journal |date=February 14, 1997 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19970719140852/http://www.lvrj.com/lvrj_home/1997/Feb-14-Fri-1997/business/4863616.html |archivedate=July 19, 1997}}</ref> As of October 1997, there were 36 stores, including a clothing store owned by Las Vegas mayor [[Jan Laverty Jones|Jan Jones]],<ref>{{cite web |last=Zapler |first=Mike |title=Jones runs business at casino she regulates |url=http://www.lvrj.com/lvrj_home/1997/Oct-09-Thu-1997/news/6205654.html |work=Las Vegas Review-Journal |date=October 9, 1997 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20000918160736/http://www.lvrj.com/lvrj_home/1997/Oct-09-Thu-1997/news/6205654.html |archivedate=September 18, 2000}}</ref> who also owned shares in Grand Casinos.<ref name=Jones/> Approximately 85 percent of the retail space was occupied, and 98 percent was leased.<ref name=\"Jones\">{{cite web |last=Zapler |first=Mike |title=Jones offers defense of casino lease |url=http://www.lvrj.com/lvrj_home/1997/Oct-16-Thu-1997/news/6248272.html |work=Las Vegas Review-Journal |date=October 16, 1997 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20000918173617/http://www.lvrj.com/lvrj_home/1997/Oct-16-Thu-1997/news/6248272.html |archivedate=September 18, 2000}}</ref>\n\nBy 1998, retailers in the Tower Shops were experiencing financial difficulties and lack of customer traffic, which the retailers blamed on the resort's unfinished facilities.<ref name=\"Retailers\">{{cite news |last=Shemeligian |first=Bob |title=Stratosphere retailers say they're hurting |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/1998/jan/26/stratosphere-retailers-say-theyre-hurting/ |accessdate=2019-07-26 |work=Las Vegas Sun |date=1998-01-26}}</ref> Strato-Retail filed suits against several of the mall's retailers, alleging non-payment of rent. Two retailers that were locked in for expensive, long-term leases filed suits against Strato-Retail.<ref name=Retailers/><ref name=\"Sued\">{{cite news |title=Retailer sued over rent |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/1999/aug/12/retailer-sued-over-rent/ |work=Las Vegas Sun |date=1999-08-12 |accessdate=2019-07-27}}</ref> As of March 1999, the Stratosphere planned to add a new escalator which the resort said would lead up to the casino's showroom. However, Strato-Retail sued Stratosphere Corporation, alleging that the escalator would hinder business to the Tower Shops by allowing visitors to bypass the mall on their way to the top of the observation tower. The resort denied that the escalator could be used to access the tower.<ref>{{cite news |title=Stratosphere sued by retailers over escalator |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/1999/mar/25/stratosphere-sued-by-retailers-over-escalator/ |work=Las Vegas Sun |date=1999-03-25 |accessdate=2019-07-27}}</ref> Strato-Retail won a permanent injunction against the escalator's construction.<ref name=Take-Over/>\n\nIn 2000, Stratosphere Corporation purchased the mall from Strato-Retail for $12.5 million.<ref>{{cite news |title=Icahn buying Stratosphere mall, taking resort private |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/2000/sep/20/icahn-buying-stratosphere-mall-taking-resort-priva/ |work=Las Vegas Sun |date=2000-09-20 |accessdate=2019-07-27}}</ref><ref name=Headache/><ref name=\"Take-Over\">{{cite news |title=Company pays $12.5 million to take over mall |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/2000/nov/13/company-pays-125-million-to-take-over-mall/ |work=Las Vegas Sun |date=2000-11-13 |accessdate=2019-07-27}}</ref> In 2004, the Tower Shops had {{convert|110000|sqft|abbr=on}} of retail space, which was approximately 90 leased. That year, the mall announced plans for an additional {{convert|80000|sqft|abbr=on}} of retail space.<ref name=Shubinski/><ref>{{cite news |last=Illia |first=Tony |title=Trade show brings rash of new project announcements |url=http://lvbusinesspress.com:80/articles/2004/05/28/columnists/col02realestate.txt |work=Las Vegas Business Press |date=2004-05-28 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040606065448/http://lvbusinesspress.com:80/articles/2004/05/28/columnists/col02realestate.txt |archivedate=2004-06-04}}</ref> The expansion would occupy undeveloped space that was meant for the Tower Shops' originally planned second phase.<ref name=\"Shubinski\">{{cite news |last=Shubinski |first=Jennifer |title=Stratosphere plans Tower Shops growth |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/2004/may/21/stratosphere-plans-tower-shops-growth/ |work=Las Vegas Sun |date=2004-05-21 |accessdate=2019-07-27}}</ref> At the time, the mall had approximately 50 stores and 15 retail carts.<ref>{{cite web |last=Smith |first=Hubble |title=Strip getting a slice of the island |url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/lvrj_home/2004/May-25-Tue-2004/business/23954996.html |work=Las Vegas Review-Journal |date=May 25, 2004 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050128011208/http://www.reviewjournal.com/lvrj_home/2004/May-25-Tue-2004/business/23954996.html |archivedate=January 28, 2005}}</ref>\n\n===Performers===\nThe casino has featured a number of performers, including bands and dancers. Frankie Moreno Live at Stratosphere had its final performance on December 20, 2014. Moreno and his 10-piece band began performing in the Stratosphere Theater on November 9, 2011 and achieved nearly 600 shows during his three-year tenure at the Stratosphere.\n\n[[Playboy Playmate]] [[List of Playboy Playmates of 2010#October|Claire Sinclair]] signed for a new show in 2013, and re-signed for 2015. David Perrico with the band Pop Evolution, signed in 2013 for a monthly show.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lasvegassun.com/blogs/kats-report/2014/dec/19/moreno-hitting-carnegie-hall-2015-wynn-gives-dance/ |title=Frankie Moreno hitting Carnegie Hall in 2015; Wynn gives 'Showstoppers' dancers room to stretch legs |website=Las Vegas Sun |date=2014-12-19 |accessdate=2016-03-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Leach |first=Robin |url=http://lasvegassun.com/vegasdeluxe/2014/dec/19/showstoppers-frankie-moreno-brian-setzer-penny-pib/ |title=Celebrity preview: 'Showstoppers,' Moreno, Setzer, Pibbets, Meryl Davis + Charlie White |website=Las Vegas Sun |date=2014-12-19 |accessdate=2016-03-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.vegaschatter.com/tag/Frankie%20Moreno |title=Things To Do In Las Vegas - Attractions & Travel Guide - Cond\u00e9 Nast Traveler |website=Vegaschatter.com |date= |accessdate=2016-03-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Hall |first=Debbie |url=http://www.axs.com/las-vegas-headliner-frankie-moreno-schedules-final-performance-at-stra-24008 |title=Las Vegas headliner Frankie Moreno schedules final performance at Stratosphere |website=AXS.com |date=2014-10-18 |accessdate=2016-03-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Mike Weatherford |url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/entertainment/entertainment-columns/mike-weatherford/pin-up-displaying-more-vintage-cool/ |title='Pin Up' displaying more vintage cool |website=Las Vegas Review-Journal |date=2014-09-01 |accessdate=2019-02-08}}</ref>\n\nThe Strat added an acrobatic show, Celestia, in June 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last=Katsilometes |first=John |title='Celestia' gathers familiar acts under one tent on Las Vegas Strip |url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/entertainment/entertainment-columns/kats/celestia-gathers-familiar-acts-under-one-tent-on-las-vegas-strip-1682244/ |accessdate=2020-01-24 |work=Las Vegas Review-Journal |date=2019-06-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Radke |first=Brock |title=The STRAT's new 'Celestia' could be a summer family hit |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/2019/jun/10/celestia-strat-circus-show-review/ |accessdate=2020-01-24 |work=Las Vegas Sun |date=2019-06-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Mills |first=Heather |title='Celestia' brings death-defying entertainment to Las Vegas Strip |url=https://news3lv.com/news/local/celestia-brings-death-defying-entertainment-to-las-vegas-strip |accessdate=2020-01-24 |work=KSNV |date=2019-12-06}}</ref> The show is performed inside a {{convert|30000|sqft|abbr=on}} tent located outside the Strat.<ref name=Schulz2/>\n\n==Dining==\n*Top of the World\n*McCall's Heartland Grill\n*Fellini's Ristorante\n*Roxy's Diner\n*The Buffet\n*Level 8 Pool Cafe\n*Tower Pizzeria\n*Starbucks\n*Level 107 Lounge\n\n==Gaming==\nSome of the casino games include [[slot machine]]s and [[video poker]]. The Stratosphere has inherited some unusual variations on casino games from its predecessor. The {{convert|80000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} casino includes 50 table games, 1,500 slot and video poker machines, a [[poker]] room, and a race and [[sports book]].\n\n==In popular culture==\n*In 1999, scenes for the game show ''[[Real World/Road Rules Challenge 2000]]'' were filmed involving contestants bungee jumping from the Stratosphere's tower.<ref name=\"Cling\">{{cite news |last=Cling |first=Carol |title=Fall TV season keeps Vegas hopping with business |url=http://www.lvrj.com/lvrj_home/1999/Sep-27-Mon-1999/lifestyles/12020643.html |work=Las Vegas Review-Journal |date=1999-09-27 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010430142649/http://www.lvrj.com/lvrj_home/1999/Sep-27-Mon-1999/lifestyles/12020643.html |archivedate=2001-04-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Clarke |first=Norm |title=MTV adventurers' wake-up call: bungee jump from Stratosphere |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/sites/lvrb/ |accessdate=2019-02-09 |work=Las Vegas Review-Journal |date=1999-09-29|url-access=subscription }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Leong |first=Grace |title=Bungee jumping resumes at Stratosphere |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/1999/sep/30/bungee-jumping-resumes-at-stratosphere/ |accessdate=2019-02-09 |work=Las Vegas Sun |date=1999-09-30}}</ref>\n*The Stratosphere was also used in 1999 for filming of the television series ''[[The Strip (U.S. TV series)|The Strip]]''.<ref name=Cling/>\n*The casino and tower are featured in the 2005 movie ''[[Domino (2005 film)|Domino]]'', in which the owner gets robbed of $10 million and the top of the tower gets damaged in an explosion.<ref>{{cite web |title=STRATOSPHERE CASINO LANDS EXPLOSIVE MOVIE PROMOTION |url=https://adage.com/article/madisonvine-case-study/stratosphere-casino-lands-explosive-movie-promotion/47196/ |website=adage.com |accessdate=7 January 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n*The tower is the inspiration for the Vertigo Spire location/map featured in the 2006 video game ''[[Tom Clancy's Rainbow Six: Vegas]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Miller |first1=Jonathan |title=Rainbow Six Vegas: A Night on the Town |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2006/11/02/rainbow-six-vegas-a-night-on-the-town |website=IGN |accessdate=7 January 2019 |date=1 November 2006}}</ref>\n*In the History Channel's ''[[Life After People]]'', the tower is destroyed by an earthquake in the 2009 episode \"Sin City Meltdown\".\n*The tower is the inspiration of the fictional Lucky 38 casino in the 2010 role-playing game ''[[Fallout: New Vegas]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Location 23: The Strip - Lucky 38 |url=http://www.falloutnewvegastour.com/2011/04/location-23-strip-lucky-38.html |accessdate=7 January 2019}}</ref>\n*In 2013, the tower was featured in episode 24 of the [[HaMerotz LaMillion 3|third season]] of the [[HaMerotz LaMillion|Israeli edition of ''The Amazing Race'']] as part of a Roadblock task where contestants had to jump off of the tower on the SkyJump.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/hamerotz/photos/a.129167740489202/513124708760168/?type=3&theater|script-title=he:\u05de\u05d9 \u05de\u05d4\u05d6\u05d5\u05d2\u05d5\u05ea \u05d9\u05e2\u05e9\u05d4 \u05d9\u05d5\u05ea\u05e8, \u05d9\u05e6\u05dc\u05d9\u05d7 \u05d9\u05d5\u05ea\u05e8 \u05d5\u05d1\u05e2\u05d9\u05e7\u05e8 \u05d9\u05d4\u05d9\u05d4 \u05d0\u05de\u05d9\u05e5 \u05d9\u05d5\u05ea\u05e8?? \u05e6\u05e4\u05d5 \u05d1\u05d4\u05e6\u05e6\u05d4 \u05dc\u05e4\u05e8\u05e7 \u05d4\u05d1\u05d0 \u05d5\u05d2\u05dc\u05d5 \u05de\u05d9 \u05de\u05d4\u05e6\u05d5\u05d5\u05ea\u05d9\u05dd \u05d4\u05ea\u05d2\u05d1\u05e8 \u05e2\u05dc \u05e4\u05d7\u05d3 \u05d4\u05d2\u05d1\u05d4\u05d9\u05dd>>|language=Hebrew|trans-title=Which of the couples will do more, be more successful and most of all be braver ?? Watch the glimpse of the next chapter and find out which team has overcome the fear of heights >>|work=[[Facebook]]|date=August 2, 2013|accessdate=December 31, 2019}}</ref>\n*In the 2014 [[Syfy]] television series ''[[Dominion (TV series)|Dominion]]'', the archangel Michael lived in the observation tower of the Stratosphere.<ref>{{cite web |title=Dominion TV show setting |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/tv/syfys-dominion-survivng-the-post-apocalypse-with-some-low-rent-angels/2014/06/18/e7670e40-f64f-11e3-a3a5-42be35962a52_story.html?noredirect=on |accessdate=7 January 2019}}</ref>\n*A replica of the tower can be found in the 2014 racing game ''[[The Crew (video game)|The Crew]]'', in the northern part of Las Vegas.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Tran |first1=Edmond |title=The Crew 2 Review - On The Road Again |url=https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/the-crew-2-review-on-the-road-again/1900-6416936/ |website=GameSpot |accessdate=7 January 2019 |date=4 July 2018}}</ref>\n*The hotel, casino and tower was featured at the beginning of the 2016 film ''[[Sharknado: The 4th Awakens]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Scene In Nevada: Sharknado 4: The 4th Awakens |url=https://nevadafilm.com/scene-in-nevada-sharknado-4-the-4th-awakens/ |website=Nevada Film Office |accessdate=7 January 2019 |date=2 May 2018}}</ref>\n*The tower appears in the video game ''[[Gangstar Vegas]]''.\n\n==Gallery==\n<center>\n<gallery>\nFile:Stratosphere view from ground level.jpg|View looking upwards at the Stratosphere\nFile:Stratosphere las vegas.jpg|View from front\nFile:Stratosphere tower at night.jpg|View from ground, inverted image\nFile:Clouds over Stratosphere Las Vegas.jpg|Clouds over the Stratosphere at midday\nFile:05 Insanity the Ride 2.jpg|Insanity, the ride atop the tower\nFile:StratoXScream.jpg|The X-Scream on top of the Stratosphere \"drops\" riders over the edge of the tower\nFile:Stratosphere roller.jpg|View of the former High Roller ride\nFile:Stratosphere Las Vegas - November 2003.jpg|Aerial view of the Stratosphere\n</gallery>\n</center>\n\n==Notes==\n{{no